<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Raise Fee for Immigrant Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government is set to
raise the cost of Canadian citizenship for foreign investors by
100,000 Canadian dollars (about 73,100 U.S. dollars) from July 1
this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the new foreign-investor program, the minimum investment
would be raised to 450,000 dollars from 350,000 dollars for those
heading to the more popular provinces such as British Columbia,
Quebec, Ontario and Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, the price for Canadian citizenship would go up to
350,000 dollars from 250,000 dollars, the Globe and Mail newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Government lawyers have been instructed to draft new rules for
the immigrant investor program.
</P>
<P>
The program, which was developed mainly to attract investors
from Hong Kong, has brought 3.75 billion dollars and almost 17,000
investors and their families to Canada since 1986, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The redesigned program will be published for public comment
before the end of this month. And the proposed increase would come
into effect July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
