<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 24th Arab Labor Conference Opens in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The 24th Arab Labor conference
opened here today at the Arab League (AL) headquarters, calling
for common strategy in tapping human resources to achieve social
development and stability in the Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
Arab labor ministers, employers and employees from all the
Arab countries attended the week-long conference, held under the
auspices of Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal al-Ganzouri.
</P>
<P>
In the opening speech, al-Ganzouri underlined the importance
of Arab integration and cooperation in order to unify stances in
face of various challenges and social problems.
</P>
<P>
Calling labor and peace two cornerstones for realizing
development and stability, he also urged the Arab countries to
draw up mechanisms to develop Arab human resources.
</P>
<P>
While inaugurating the conference, Esmat Abdul-Meguid,
secretary general of the 22-member AL, hailed the envisaged Arab
free trade zone as a first step on the road to realizing Arab
economic integration.
</P>
<P>
The AL's economic council ratified last week the executive
program of the regional free trade zone which is to be
established in 1998. The exact boundary of the zone is yet to be
defined.
</P>
<P>
He underscored the link between development and labor in
pushing forward comprehensive development efforts.
</P>
<P>
"Human resources are one of the pillars of economic
development, which requires good preparation and adjustment in
order to cope with economic development needs," said the AL chief.
</P>
<P>
In his address at the conference, Director General of the Arab
Labor Organization Bakr Mahmoud Rasoul also stressed the
importance of establishing the Arab common market to boost Arab
solidarity and integration.
</P>
<P>
He said the current session is held at a time when the Arab
world is going through the "most critical stage" in light of
ongoing globalization of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Rasoul said he will submit a report for deliberations at the
session on development, economic conditions in the Arab world,
development barriers and ways to upgrade vocational training and
create more jobs to the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Bank's estimates, Arab labor force has
reached around 80 million workers out of the region's total
population of over 200 million, with an unemployment rate of 14
percent. The Arab Gross Domestic Product (GDP) exceeded 502
billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
