<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Calls for Faster Development in Central, Western China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some regions with better conditions may enjoy faster
development, which will in turn help the country to accumulate
funds and increase its economic strength, and help areas with
poorer conditions to speed up their development gradually, and
eventually to achieve common prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Practice has shown that this strategist decision made Comrade
Deng Xiaoping is totally correct, which not only comply with the
law of economic development, but also fully reflect the
fundamental requirements of socialism, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that common prosperity for all the regions across
China cannot be achieved overnight, and it requires a process and
the joint efforts nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to its wide-ranged exchanges and cooperation with
Shanghai municipality, and Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Fujian and Jiangxi
provinces, Ningxia has achieved positive results.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the wish that the autonomous region will continue
such cooperations and promote common development and prosperity
through further opening-up by both sides and still closer
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia is one of the five autonomous regions with ethnic
groups in China, he said, and it is of utmost importance to
enhance ethnic unity, safeguard social stability to promote
development in the national minorities region.
</P>
<P>
Jiang emphasized that governments in ethnic regions must pay
much attention to doing a good job in handling the religious
issue. The Party's policies concerning religious affairs fully
respect and protect ethnic peoples' freedom for religious belief.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, religious activities must be conducted within
the limits as provided by the constitution and laws, and
administration of religious affairs should be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
During its meeting the Gansu delegation, Jiang said Gansu has
scored new successes in reform and construction, in view of the
province's economic growth rate topping for the first time the
national average in 1996 and the accomplishment of its second-step
strategic goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
