<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Humanitarian Groups Withdraw from Key Zairean Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINSHASA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The first group of 26
international humanitarian groups working in Kisangani, the
capital of Upper Zaire which has served as the basis of
humanitarian aid for Rwandan refugees since late last year,
arrived here today on a plane.
</P>
<P>
The members of humanitarian aid groups said that all the Hutu
refugees have fled the refugee camp of Tingi-Tingi near the city,
as the rebel forces led by Laurent-Desire Kabila are reportedly
approaching the city.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Zairean government today denied the claim by the
rebels that Kindu, the capital of the Maniema province south of
Kisangani, has fallen and said that it is always controlled by the
government forces, the FAZ.
</P>
<P>
A communique of the Zairean Defense Ministry also denied that
Kisangani is under the threat of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
It said that the FAZ is reinforcing necessary forces to move
toward Kalima, a town 50 to 60 kilometers northwest of Kindu which
has fallen to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the FAZ has taken prisoner 50 Ugandans,
Rwandans and Zaireans in Bafwasende, some 200 kilometers east of
Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
The rebel forces claimed that they are within 100 kilometers of
Kisangani. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
