<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia's FUNCINPEC Deplores CPP's Boycott to United Front </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Phnom Penh, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's FUNCINPEC Party said
today that it felt regretful for the boycott by the Cambodian
People's Party (CPP) to the political platform of the newly formed
National United Front (NUF).
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued to the press, the FUNCINPEC Party said
it was "very regretful for the total rejection by the CPP to the
NUF platform which covers a lot of vital issues such as the state
of law, the neutrality of the administration, the national
sovereignty and integrity and illegal immigration."
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the FUNCINPEC also regretted for the
CPP's misunderstanding and confusion of an interview given by
First Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh, who is also leader
of the FUNCINPEC and president of the NUF.
</P>
<P>
The communique came after the CPP, that formed an uneasy
coalition government with FUNCINPEC following the U.N.-run
elections in 1993, issued a statement earlier today to respond an
interview by Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
During the interview Ranariddh said he did not invite the CPP
to the NUF's inaugural congress because he heard that CPP's Vice
Chairman Hun Sen had declared rejection to join the NUF.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh added he would choose appropriate time to meet CPP
Chairman Chea Sim and hand over the NUF platform.
</P>
<P>
The CPP's statement reiterated its stance to boycott the NUF,
saying it had no need to examine the NUF's political platform.
</P>
<P>
The FUNCINPEC communique said Ranariddh, in the interview,
showed his respect for Chea Sim and regarded the CPP as his ally,
but the CPP has confused this with an evil intent.
</P>
<P>
The communique also rejected CPP's accusation against
FUNCINPEC's alliance with opposition party, saying that was its
full right to choose partners as it did not request the opposition
party to work in the current government.
</P>
<P>
The communique chided the CPP for provoking problems and
"causing political instability."
</P>
<P>
The NUF, a political alliance which was officially launched on
February 27, brings together the FUNCINPEC Party, the Khmer Nation
party and the Khmer Neutral Party and a faction of the divided
Buddhist Liberal Democratic Party led by Son Sann. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
