<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Belarus to Hold Referendums on Reunification: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and Belarus President Alexander Lukashenko have agreed in principle
to hold referendums in the two countries on their reunification,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin will announce the plan next Thursday in his address to
parliament, Interfax news agency quoted Kremlin sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Yeltsin, in a January letter to
Lukashenko, proposed holding simultaneous national referendums, or
something like it, on closer integration between the two ex-Soviet
republics.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko, an ardent supporter of reunification with
Russia, reportedly agreed to the proposal, adding that
"supranational power" should be given to the committee in charge
of integration.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders signed a deal last April to create a
"community" with closer political and economic links, and to set
up supranational governing bodies.
</P>
<P>
The move, if successfully carried out, would combine the two
countries into a new state with one central government, one
currency and one budget, their economic systems fully merged.
</P>
<P>
The report said Yeltsin has been impatient with the slow paces
towards a union and called for more resolute actions, saying a
reunification would benefit both countries significantly.
</P>
<P>
Observers say the timing of the move is linked to the upcoming
NATO summit in July, when the alliance is expected to name the
first wave of eastern and central European countries to be
admitted in it.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been bitterly opposed to NATO's eastward expansion to
its borders, viewing it as a grave threat to its national security.
</P>
<P>
Belarus, split from Russia in 1991 when former Soviet Union
dissolved, has remained the stanchest ally of Russia among all the
ex-Soviet republics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
