<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mock Air Crash Causes Chaos In Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Hospital chiefs were furious Friday
night after they were involved in a mock airline disaster without
being told.
</P>
<P>
The Norfolk and Norwich Hospital went on alert after its
switchboard was flooded with "relatives" asking about victims of a
major air crash, British media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Medical teams and paramedics were contacted by the hospital,
which was on the point of canceling routine operations to make way
for the air victims.
</P>
<P>
When health officials eventually discovered the truth, they
branded the exercise by AirUK as "extremely irresponsible."
</P>
<P>
Louise Zucchi, spokeswoman for the hospital, said, "We were not
told about it and our casualty staff had no way of knowing it was
an exercise when the calls started coming in."
</P>
<P>
"They were obviously concerned they were facing a major
incident and took it seriously," she added.
</P>
<P>
The emergency exercise was organized for AirUK by former
reporter Jeremy Hands, whose company specializes in "crisis
management" training.
</P>
<P>
He recruited more than 30 students from a journalism college to
help.
</P>
<P>
"Like the AirUK personnel involved, they were put under
realistic pressure within the boundaries of the exercise," Hands
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
