<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Labor Outlines Plans for Early Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain's opposition Labor Party
today outlined plans for a post election "welfare-to-work" budget,
pledging to eradicate the nightmare of young people facing a
lifetime without work.
</P>
<P>
In a speech detailing Labor's early spending plans should it
win the coming election, its leader Tony Blair said that
unemployed people would not be allowed to turn down all jobs and
keep benefit.
</P>
<P>
The Budget would introduce a windfall utilities tax and give
firms a 75 pounds (120 US dollars) per week tax rebate for taking
on someone unemployed long term, he told a conference.
</P>
<P>
"For today's school leavers there will be no lifetime on the
dole under Labor," Blair said. "We simply cannot continue with a
situation where today unemployment costs the country more than
education."
</P>
<P>
However Blair explained the aim of the program was not to raise
public spending but to reduce it.
</P>
<P>
Blair, whose party is now some 20 points ahead of the ruling
Conservatives in opinion polls, said it had a been a "landmark
week" for Labor thanks to its victory in the key Wirral South
by-election.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Major was forced to admit in an interview
with ITN yesterday that "if opinion does not change, then we are
going to have a Labor government".
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the "welfare-to-work" Budget, Chancellor of the
Exchequer Kenneth Clarke said it was disingenuous to suppose they
would produce a reduction in welfare spending.
</P>
<P>
"It is Mickey Mouse arithmetic," Clarke told Sky News. "It is a
large public spending package. It is a large new tax...that has
the effect of driving up industrial costs," the Chancellor added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
