<HEADLINE> Mugabe to Visit Britain, France, Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
leaves Harare on Sunday on a three-nation tour that will take him
to Britain, France and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
A statement released here today by the Foreign Ministry said
on the first leg of his tour, Mugabe will lead a powerful
government and private sector delegation to the London investment
conference on Zimbabwe to be held on March 5.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe will also hold talks with British Prime Minister John
Major and other high-ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
Britain is the largest foreign investor in Zimbabwe, with some
300 companies having total investments of about 636 million U.S.
Dollars. It is also Zimbabwe's largest export destination and the
country's second largest source of imports.
</P>
<P>
From Britain, Mugabe will proceed to France where he will hold
talks with his French counterpart Jacques Chirac, whom he will be
meeting for the first time since the latter became president in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe's visit to Ireland will be marked at a keynote address
to a Harvard University-Irish Times colloquium on the topic:
''Africa: Recognition of the Past, Remedies for the Future''. He
will also hold talks with Irish President Mary Robinson and Prime
Minister John Bruton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
