<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Police on Violence in Mutare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 1 (xinhua) -- Police in Mutare, the largest city
in east Zimbabwe arrested at least 16 people following violence
at a show by Paris-based Rhumba musician Sakis at Sakubva stadium
last night, the Zimbabwe national news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
A number of people were assaulted outside the stadium and
others had their car windscreens smashed by youths who were
complaining that the 50 Zimbabwe Dollars (4.5 U.S. Dollars) entry
fee was too high.
</P>
<P>
Officer-in-charge of Sakubva police station, Inspector Beven
Tungwarare, who confirmed the incident, said 10 other people were
hospitalized after being bitten by guard dogs unleashed by
security guards trying to quell the violence.
</P>
<P>
He said the youths first gathered outside the stadium gates
before going to Sakubva main bus terminus and nearby round-about
where they used rocks to block the road leading to the stadium
and started smashing windscreens of passing vehicles and
assaulting people.
</P>
<P>
Some of those who were arrested would appear in court as soon
as police completed their investigations, he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 people were arrested at the same stadium in 1992
for violence during a show staged by a British group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
