<HEADLINE> Woman Condemned to Death for Genocide in Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 1 (Xinhua) -- A Rwandan court Friday condemned a
woman to death for participating in the genocide against Tutsis
and moderate Hutus in 1994, said a report of the Agence
France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
Virginie Mukankusi was the first woman to appear in court in
what is called ``genocide trial'' of Rwanda which began in late
December, said AFP.
</P>
<P>
So far the Rwandan judicial authorities have given death
sentences to 13 people for the massacre of at least 500,000 people
from April to July, 1994.
</P>
<P>
Mukankusi, who appeared first on January 30 at a specialized
chamber of the tribunal of first investigation of Gitarama, was
convicted of acts of genocide, assassinations, lootings and
destructions.
</P>
<P>
Her profession and age were not disclosed by the Rwandan
national radio, which announced the news today.
</P>
<P>
Some 90,000 people are waiting for trial over charges of
genocide in Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
