<HEADLINE> Consultative Conference to Be Held in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's opposition Front for
Popular Democracy plans to organize a national consultative
conference in August to seek ways to work with the government to
promote democracy in the country.
</P>
<P>
Front President Austin Chakaodza said in a statement today
that his party would challenge Robert Mugabe and his government
to start the process of democratization in Zimbabwe through the
holding of a national constitutional conference in order to draw
up a new permanent and democratic constitution for the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the aim of the conference would be to formally
approach the government and demand that a national constitutional
conference be held to map out new rules and regulations for
promoting democracy and for the conduct of parliamentary,
presidential and local government elections.
</P>
<P>
The comments came in the wake of government calls for
increased networking among government, opposition parties and
non-governmental organizations in educating society on democracy
and good governance, who attended a Commonwealth roundtable
summit on democracy in Botswana last week. 
