<HEADLINE> S. Africa Urges Warring Parties in Zaire to Stop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa today called on
the rebels and government troops in Zaire to suspend hostilities
during their peace talks in Pretoria, the administrative capital
of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the South African government called on Zairean
rebels headed by Laurent Kabila and the Zairean government to
"refrain from military operation in the days to come."
</P>
<P>
"Continued hostilities would only serve to undermine the
initial steps now underway to find a peaceful solution to the
present crisis in eastern Zaire," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Kabila and Honore Ngbanda, envoy of Zairean President Mobuto
Sese Seko left South Africa on Friday after attending peace talks
mediated by President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Kabila will consult members of his alliance on the four days
of discussions while Ngbanda returned to Kinshasa, capital of
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Zairean rebels launched an offensive last October in a bid to
topple Mobutu's 31-year-rule after the government tried to expel
ethnic Tutsis who had been there in the last two centuries, from
eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here today, while the rebel
leaders were ready for direct peace negotiations, the Zairean
government said it would not hold face-to-face talks until
"foreign troops" -- allegedly from Rwanda and Uganda -- withdraw
from Zaire. 
</P>
