<HEADLINE> Cyprus Rejects U.S. Claims About Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today strongly rejected
the U.S. State Department claim that Cyprus is a high risk area
for money laundering.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus News Agency quoted Governor of the Cyprus Central
Bank Afxentis Afxentiou as saying that Cyprus has already taken
many measures against money laundering and is making them
effective.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on the annual International Narcotics Control
report of the U.S. State Department which shifts Cyprus from a
medium-high to a high priority country, in the money laundering
section.
</P>
<P>
The bank chief encouraged any person in the know on money
laundering in his country to speak, "so that we can take specific
measures."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus approved in 1996 a new law to combat money laundering,
Afxentiou said, adding his bank has already begun implementing it.
</P>
<P>
Afxentiou added that local banks have been instructed to be
more strict in the identification of prospective customers,
before they open an account or transfer money through accounts.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that Cyprus has already set up a financial
intelligence unit comprising a representative from the Attorney
General's office, the Customs department and the police, to
enforce the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
