<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Government Stops Funding For Sheep Cloning Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Agriculture Ministry
decided today to cut off funding for the project that produced
Dolly, the first cloned sheep in the world, according to the
scientists involved in the research.
</P>
<P>
The team that made the breakthrough at the Roslin Institute in
Edinburgh is said to be "despondent".
</P>
<P>
Ministers, newspapers and even prominent scientists such as
Nobel Peace Prize winner Joseph Rotblat have raised the specter of
mad scientists using the Roslin technology to create carbon copies
of dictators, film stars or millionaires.
</P>
<P>
It is announced that the government funding -- currently
252,000 pounds (403,000 US dollars) -- will be halved next month
and withdrawn in April next year.
</P>
<P>
With money short, there are fears of redundancies which could
mean scientists being poached by rival teams abroad who are trying
to catch up.
</P>
<P>
"We had the formal letter on February 27," said Grahame
Bulfield, director of the institute. "At the moment 65 percent of
the work in Ian Wilmut's lab is supported by MAFF (the Ministry of
Agriculture, Fisheries and Food)," he added. "It's a major
problem."
</P>
<P>
One of the scientist in the team speculated that the ministry
had been made so uncomfortable by the debate on the possibility of
cloning humans that it decided to axe much of the biotechnology
research it sponsors at Roslin.
</P>
<P>
A  spokesman for the ministry said: "If they have researched
what they were supposed to have researched, then that's it...The
funding will come to an end."
</P>
<P>
The Roslin Institute has a close partnership with biotechnology
company PPL Therapeutids Plc, which holds licences for some of the
work being done there -- the genetic engineering of animals to
produce human proteins for use in medicines.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has argued that backing should come from industry
but Prof Bulofied said that there were long term applications of
the technology in animal breeding, which is of direct concern to
the ministry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
