<HEADLINE> Palestinian Council Calls for General Strike Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Council (PC)
today called for a general strike Monday across the Palestinian
territories in protest against Israel's decision to build a new
Jewish settlement in Jebel Abu Ghneim (Har Homa) in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The 88-member Palestinian legislature met in an emergency
session in the West Bank city of Ramallah to discuss how to react
to the new settlement plan.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet Ministerial Committee on Jerusalem Affairs
decided to approve the construction of a new settlement in Har
Homa with 6,500 housing units. The decision triggered off
furious reaction from the Palestinians and also aroused a
worldwide condemnation.
</P>
<P>
The Har Homa issue was taken up at a joint meeting of
the Palestinian National Authority and PLO Executive Committee in
Gaza Friday night. An open letter, issued at the end of the
meeting, warned that the new settlement drive will destroy the
Middle East peace process and Israel should bear responsibility
for any violence resulting from the construction.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat today traveled to Cairo to
hold consultations with President Hisni Mubarak and Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa on Israel's settlement policy and the new
settlement plan in particular.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who also had a lengthy telephone discussion with King
Hussein of Jordan Friday, is scheduled to fly to Washington next
week to meet President Bill Clinton and senior government
officials. The settlement issue is expected to be high on agenda.
</P>
<P>
Several hundreds of left-wing Israelis and Palestinians this
afternoon marched from Beit Sahur to Har Homa settlement site
in protest against the construction.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration was organized by Gush Shalom (the Peace
Bloc) and other peace groups alongside various Palestinian
political and social groups. A number of Palestinian ministers
and PC members also participated in the protest march.
</P>
<P>
Gush Shalom said in a press statement that the demonstration is
intended to underline the determination of all participants,
Israeli as well as Palestinian, to block the Government of
Israel's provocative action which seriously threatens the future
of peace between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
In Ramallah, meanwhile, several hundred Palestinians took to
the street against Israeli occupation. During the demonstration,
organized by the Popular Front for Liberation of Palestine,
participants burned pictures of Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
