<HEADLINE> Kenya, Tanzania Succeed in Rinderpest Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and Tanzania have succeeded
in controlling a rinderpest outbreak hitting Kajiado district of
Kenya and adjacent parts of Tanzania since last November,
according to a Kenya News Agency report today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Kenyan veterinary officer Cleophas Kogo as
saying that a quarantine effected in January this year to
restrict movement of cattle in and out of Kajiado district might
be lifted soon.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the vaccination against the disease in two weeks
time, he noted, a total of 400,000 head of cattle will have been
vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
Kogo pointed out that without the cooperation between the two
countries, the campaign would have been hampered by migrations of
Kenya's livestock to areas for greener pastures in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Most cattle from the Kenyan side crossing the border in search
of greener pasture have been vaccinated by Tanzanian veterinary
officials, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Following the rinderpest outbreak originated from wildlife in
Tsavo West and Nairobi National Parks, vaccination teams were
mobilized last November to trail pastoralists to the dry season
grazing areas in a bid to get all animals vaccinated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
