<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 502 in Quake in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of an earthquake
which hit northwest Iran Friday afternoon has risen to 502 and the
number of the injured to 2,000, the latest official report said
today.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that 56 villages
with a total population of 45,000 have been partly or largely
damaged as the result of the quake.
</P>
<P>
The quake measuring six degrees on the Richter scale stroke
cities of Ardebil and Meshkin Shahr and their surrounding
villages -- about 600 kilometers northwest of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Relief teams continue operations to rescue survivors of the
quake which occurred at 16:31 hours local time (13:01 GMT)
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the tremor, which lasted for about 15
seconds, panicked people and drove them out into the streets.
</P>
<P>
Several aftershocks followed the tremor.
</P>
<P>
This is the second major earthquake within a month. On
February 4, another quake measuring 6.1 degrees on the Richter
scale jolted northern Khorasan province, killing a total of 86
people and injuring hundreds of others.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 village suffered varying degrees of destruction,
some totally razed. Over 11,000 houses were damaged, forcing
thousands to become homeless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
