<HEADLINE> Kenya Encourages Privatization in Livestock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
encouraged privatization in livestock services since 1991 as part
of economic liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Second Annual General Meeting of the Kenya
Livestock Breeders which opened today in Nakuru, about 165 km
northwest of capital Nairobi, Agricultural Minister Darious Mbela
said the government had identified services that needed to be
privatized and those to remain in the ministry.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government had handed over the management of
cattle dips to dip management committees in 1991 and provided
free acaricides with the aim of having the dip committees build a
revolving fund.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister added, the program collapsed as a result
of depreciation of the Kenyan currency of Shillings in 1993 which
eroded their accounts.
</P>
<P>
Before 1993, there were more than 6,000 dips throughout the
country owned by farmers and communities, out of which 4,100 were
run by dip management committees.
</P>
<P>
The minister announced the revival of dip services following
the signing of a contract for the supply of acaricides and
training of dip management committees by the government,
according to a Kenya News Agency report today.
</P>
<P>
The government has since 1991 been stressing the privatization
of the veterinary clinical services in high livestock production
areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, 300 clinical centers are in operation in the east
African country while 164 private veterinarians have been
assisted to enter into private practice.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Veterinary Project is being expanded to attract
unemployed and retired veterinarians to start clinics in major
dairy production areas.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that artificial insemination carried out by
private practitioners increased from 8,248 in 1992 to 100,000
last year.
</P>
<P>
The government will gradually withdraw artificial insemination
services from well served areas by the private sector and moved
to promote the same in other areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
