<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quebec's Unilateral Secession Illegal, Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The province of Quebec has no right
under domestic or international law to secede unilaterally from
the confederation, the federal government has argued before the
Supreme Court of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The government said that Quebecers have a right to separate if
they choose. But the only way to ensure a lawful, orderly and
peaceful divorce would be by negotiating a constitutional
amendment approved by the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
"Without the rule of law, there is a high risk of uncertainty,
instability and arbitrariness in the exercise of governmental
power," the government was quoted as saying by today's reports.
</P>
<P>
The factum presented before the court Friday is believed to be
the first step by the federal government to ensure that Quebec
never again sets all the rules for a referendum or subsequently
separation process.
</P>
<P>
It sets out the most detailed arguments from the government
since it decided last September to ask the Supreme Court of Canada
to rule on the legality of unilateral separation.
</P>
<P>
A full hearing on the case is not expected before this Autumn
and a decision by the court seems unlikely before the next federal
election, which is widely anticipated to take place as early as
June.
</P>
<P>
Quebec has indicated that it will not participate in the court
hearings, arguing that the question of independence will be
settled not by judges, but by the people through vote in a
referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
