<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Three hundred people, led by the
Socialist mayor of Strasbourg Catherine Trautmann, today staged a
street protest against a plan by the far-right National Front (FN)
party to hold a congress in the eastern French city.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported that the demonstrators
gathered in the center of the city at the call of a local anti-FN
group, "Citizens' Front," to sign a petition against the holding
of FN congress.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted Francois Guichard, vice-president of "Citizen's
Front," as saying that 15,000 signatures were obtained, including
those from Mayor Trautmann and Nobel Peace Prize winner Elie
Wiesel, artists, sportsman and political figures.
</P>
<P>
Trautmann also signed a "charter of foreign residents" to
call on the public to mobilize against FN, which she said is "a
party that advocates racism, xenophobia, and social disorder."
</P>
<P>
"Your mobilization will be a civil and civic expression in the
respect of a national and European conscience for the democratic
values and against a party which advocates civil war," she said.
</P>
