<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Firms Expected to Bottom Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- China's state firms are expected
to bottom out this year but their difficult situation is not
likely to improve significantly in the near future,
</P>
<P>
There will be a trend of overall improving economic performance
for state-owned enterprises this year and, expectedly, such a
tendency will get stronger in the next few years, said deputies to
the on-going fifth session of the Eighth National People's
Congress, China's legislature.
</P>
<P>
The forecast is justified by a recent national survey by the
State Statistical Bureau, which said that this year sales will
increase or remain the same as last year for most state firms.
</P>
<P>
But the deputies also warned that the current situation where
state enterprises are plagued by various difficulties will not
improve considerably.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the government should promote the development of
state firms by accelerating the pace of reforming the economic
system.
</P>
<P>
The difficulties of China's state firms have worsened in recent
years and peaked last year, when over 40 percent of them were in
the red by year-end.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Huang Da, an economist, said that the state firms' weak
competitiveness due to vestiges of a planned economy is the main
factor accounting for their difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Other factors include too much administrative intervention, too
much debt, outdated equipment and technology, and poor management.
</P>
<P>
Joining the delegation from Shanghai, China's largest
industrial center, Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo said Saturday that over
40 percent of the financially-independent state enterprises
lost money in the first quarter of last year but made money in the
second quarter, with profits growing in later months.
</P>
<P>
"Our state firms have passed their most difficult year," Wu
said. "This demonstrates that their ability to adapt to macro
economic reforms and to the market has improved."
</P>
<P>
As more reform measures will be unveiled and implemented, the
performance of state-owned enterprises will further improve, the
Vice-Premier said.
</P>
<P>
Gu Yongde, a deputy from the old industrial base of Liaoning
Province, said that measures taken to reform state firms since
1995 have begun to show results.
</P>
<P>
Shi Jiwen, a deputy from Shenyang Air-Blower Plant, said that
more and more state-owned enterprises are turning to the market
for a way out and are striving to improve their efficiency.
</P>
<P>
"Such endeavors will be effective," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to reforms in economic operation and to industrial
restructuring, the textile industry in Shanghai has gone out of
losses in the past two years and begun to make money.
</P>
<P>
Ye Gongqi, chairman of the Standing Committee of Shanghai
Municipal People's Congress, predicted that reforms in state firms
will score greater achievements this year.
</P>
<P>
Economist Huang Da echoed Ye, saying that "reforms in China's
state firms have embarked on a right track and all problems and
difficulties will be resolved ultimately."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
