<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Clone Monkeys from Embryos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists have produced
two monkeys from cloned embryos in the use of a technique similar
to the one that Scottish researchers cloned an adult sheep, The
Washington Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The two monkeys, born in August, were cloned from cells taken
from embryos so they are not genetically identical to any adult
monkey -- a crucial difference between them and Dolly, the sheep
cloned by the Scottish researchers, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Leader researcher Don Wolf, a senior scientist at the Oregon
Regional Primate Research Center and director of a human in vitro
fertilization laboratory, said researchers do not plan to produce
clones from adult monkeys.
</P>
<P>
"This is really an effort to see if we can create generically
identical monkeys for research," the Post quoted the researcher as
saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the success in Oregon, the first time a species so
closely related to humans has been cloned, adds to a growing body
of evidence that there are no insurmountable biological barriers
to create multiple copies of a human being.
</P>
<P>
"Last week we knew sheep could be cloned, this week we got the
news about monkey, then how about next week? human being?" a talk
show host warned in his radio program this morning.
</P>
<P>
The two monkeys are not identical to each other because they
were from different embryos. But researchers said the technique
could be used to create eight or more identical monkeys from a
single embryo, and that further advances could lead to the ability
to make clones of adult monkeys as well.
</P>
<P>
The monkeys were created in a two-step technique. First,
researchers created several monkey embryos using a standard in
vitrorch fertilization method of mixing eggs from a single female
with sperm. Once the embryos had divided into eight cells, Wolf
and his colleagues teased apart the cells.
</P>
<P>
In the second step, the scientists took one full set of
chromosomes from each embryo cell and inserted each batch into a
fresh egg cell whose DNA had been removed. Each of those cells
then had the potential to become a new embryos.
</P>
<P>
Then the successfully developed embryos would be implanted into
female monkeys. Using this method , scientists made three monkeys
become pregnant, two of them successfully bore baby monkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislators on Steel Output (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- When Premier Li Peng announced in
his government work report that China's steel output last year
exceeded 100 million tons, Wang Peizhou felt a surging pride.
</P>
<P>
"This is the result of painstaking efforts by several
generations of people," said Wang, vice-chairman of the board of
the Baosteel Group in east China's Shanghai, and a deputy to the
Eighth National People's Congress, China's legislature, which is
having its fifth session in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Wang's feeling was shared by many other legislators, who
believed that the 1996 steel output is an important milestone in
China's industrialization process as well as an indication that
the country's comprehensive economic strength has ascended to a
new height.
</P>
<P>
China's iron and steel industry started in 1890, but its annual
steel output in 1949 was merely 158,000 tons. After the founding
of New China, steel output rose steadily and reached 5.35 million
tons in 1957.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s, the central government decided to make steel
production a top industrial priority, and set the objective
of beating Britain and the United States in steel output. This led
to a fanatic steelmaking campaign nationwide, which caused huge
losses and ended in failure.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Shi Mingyang, a senior engineering from China's
largest iron and steel enterprise -- the Anshan Steel Company in
northeast China's Liaoning Province, noted that although the
"steelmaking campaign" was against law of economic development, it
also reflected Chinese leaders' special interest in developing the
steel industry.
</P>
<P>
"The late Chairman Mao Zedong once pointed out that grain and
steel are the two things most important for China's development," he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
Since reform and opening up started in 1978, China's iron
and steel industry has enjoyed rapid progress, with a steel
output of over 60 million tons in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislators on Steel Output (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1990, however, Deng Xiaoping said: "Only when the output
reaches 100 to 120 million tons will China have enough steel to
use. This is a problem concerning the strategy of development."
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China produced 101.1 million tons of steel, and
became the world's No.1 steel manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's iron and steel industry has kept on
improving its internal structure and product quality, and has been
able to produce most kinds of steel needed in various sectors of
the national economy.
</P>
<P>
"To date, we have succeeded in developing and supplying a lot
of key metals for the defense industry and some top technologies,"
claimed Shi, adding that this reflects the continuous improvement
of China's national strength.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Wu Renbao, a farmer from the Huaxi Village in east
China's Jiangsu Province, described grain and steel as "two
pillars" of the country.
</P>
<P>
"Grain production in the agricultural sector and steel output
in the industrial sector are two important material bases for
national development," he noted.
</P>
<P>
As one of the managers of the country's most modernized steel
enterprise, Wang Peizhou held that China still has a long way to
go before it can be called a steel giant.
</P>
<P>
"We have caught up with other countries in steel output, but
still fall far behind international big names in terms of product
structure and quality," he explained.
</P>
<P>
His view echoed a plan set forth by the Ministry of
Metallurgical Industry for a further development of the iron and
steel industry.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the ministry said that while trying to maintain an
adequate growth of output, China's steel industry in future will
focus on upgrading technologies and equipment, restructuring
enterprises and the product mix, reducing energy consumption, and
raising efficiency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
