<HEADLINE> NPC Deputies Uphold Government's Taiwan Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Deputies to the fifth session of
the Eighth National People's Congress, China's legislature, said
that they firmly support the Chinese government's stance of
opposing "Taiwan independence".
</P>
<P>
In a panel discussion of Premier Li Peng's government work
report delivered to the current NPC session on Saturday, Lin
Liyun, an NPC deputy representing Taiwan, noted that Premier Li
Peng quoted in his report President Jiang Zemin's "Eight Points"
proposal on developing relations across the Taiwan Strait and
promoting peaceful reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
"This fully demonstrates the sincerity of the Chinese
Government in properly resolving the Taiwan issue," said Lin, who
is a member of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government will resume the exercise of its
sovereignty over Hong Kong this summer under the guideline of "one
country, two systems" and is confident in maintaining prosperity
and stability in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's smooth return to the motherland and prosperity
will make the masses of compatriots in Taiwan believe that 'one
country, two systems' is practical and feasible," Lin said.
</P>
<P>
"In regard with whether relations across the Strait can be
developed," she said, the crux of the matter hinges on the
attitude of the Taiwan authorities," she noted.
</P>
<P>
Wang Ansheng, an NPC deputy of Taiwan origin from eastern Anhui
Province, said that Premier Li Peng's report stresses on a focal
point of perseverence in unity, opposition to separation, and
urges the Taiwan authorities to adopt the stance of following the
historical trend and safeguarding the interests of the Chinese
nation.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, many NPC deputies have voiced their
position to prompt the Taiwan authorities to give up as early as
possible the stance of preventing "three direct links", namely,
the direct mail, trade and shipping services across the Taiwan
Strait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
