<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 554 in Quake in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of an earthquake
which jolted northwest Iran Friday afternoon rose to 554 until
this morning, the official IRNA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Rasul Zargar, head of the Interior Ministry's headquarters
for natural disasters, said that some 83 villages with a total
population of 35,000 people sustained severe damages.
</P>
<P>
The report said that more than 2,000 people are suffering
injuries from the earthquake measuring six degrees on the Richter
scale which stroke cities of Ardebil and Meshkin Shahr and their
surrounding villages, about 600 kilometers northwest of Tehran, at
16:31 hours local time (13:01 GMT) Friday.
</P>
<P>
Extensive relief operations are currently underway in the
quake-stricken areas. The quake has reportedly left thousands of
people homeless in the mountainous region, west of the Caspian
Sea, parts of which are cut off as the region is covered
with thick snow.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers from the army and Iran's Red Crescent
Society as well as volunteers have managed to reach some parts
of the quake-hit areas with temperature of minus 20 degrees
Celsius.
</P>
<P>
So far large amounts of food, medicines, tents and floor
coverings have been distributed among the quake victims by
some 400 relief workers.
</P>
<P>
The quake was followed by several aftershocks. Meanwhile an
earthquake measuring four on the Richter scale hit regions in
northeastern Iran on Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
