<HEADLINE> Disaster-Relief Work in Quake-stricken Part of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Rescue and disaster-relief work has
begun in Jiashi County of Kashgar, in northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, which was hit by an earthquake measuring
6.0 on the Richter Scale at 14:04 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
This was the most recent of a series of shocks that have hit
Jiashi County since early this year, and the third that registered
above 6.0 on the Richter Scale in the county within a year.
</P>
<P>
So far, the quake has claimed one life, and wounded six
people. It also killed 738 head of cattle and destroyed about
4,000 homes and seven mosques.
</P>
<P>
Li Donghui, vice-chairman of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, visited the county soon after the earthquake happened to
coordinate rescue and disaster relief work, and other high-ranking
officials have gone to the area to help with the work.
</P>
<P>
The local government of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
are having 1,000 tons of coal shipped to the county and local
officials are helping people rebuild their lives and prepare for
spring planting.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Regional Seismological Bureau earlier predicted
that strong aftershocks might occur in the county, and told local
government and residents to take precautions.
</P>
<P>
Quake experts believe that an aftershock measuring more than
5.0 on the Richter Scale may still happen within a week. The two
previous strong earthquakes claimed 36 lives and injured 170
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
