<HEADLINE> S. Africa's DP Declines to Join Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 2 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Demoratic Party
(DP) today declined an offer by President Nelson Mandela to join the
government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
DP leader Tony Leon told a press conference that conditions
proposed by Mandela for the DP's participation in the cabinet
would have made it impossible for the party to continue
effectively as an opposition party.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of the president's proposal, debate and discusssion on
key policy issues would have had to take place behind closed doors
and away from public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
"The DP would have been bound by cabinet decisions and collective
cabinet responsibility and thus be unable to play the role of a
vigorous, probing critical opposition," Leon said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Leon made the remarks after a two-day meeting of the party's
Federal Council in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the DP's future role, Leon said his party would
continue to put forward proposals on key issues such as economic
growth, job creation, crime prevention, the promotion of fundamental
human rights and the protection of the constitituion.
</P>
<P>
Leon said during recent discusssions with Mandela he
indciated that the DP would continue to promote constructive,
positive and practical solutions to problems facing South Africa.
