<HEADLINE> McRac Took Lead at Safari Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Briton Colin McRae took the lead
at the Safari Rally with four hours 41 minuts and 21 seconds after
completing a 25-section-run second leg, round three of world
series here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
McRae had an oil leak from his power steering while local
driver Ian Duncan's front struts are still faulty on Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Finn driver Tommi Makinen, 1996's world champion and Safari
winner, retired as his Mitsubishi car had three punctures on the
first competitive section.
</P>
<P>
Makinen's car motored on a flat and with transmission troubles
for about 40 kilometers but finally quit 23 kilometers before the
Elburgon control.
</P>
<P>
The road leader of the rally, regardly widely as the toughest
event on world championships calendar, has changed at least four
times in a dramatic start to the second day of the event.
</P>
<P>
Overnight leader German Armin Schwarz broke the rear suspension
of his Ford Escort, leaving the Subaru Impreza of McRae swept into
the lead with a storming run across the 2,500 meters high Mau
Escarpment.
</P>
<P>
Schwarz and his navigator Denis Giraudet finally had to stop
and replace a rear shock-absorber themselves in mid-section.
</P>
<P>
World championship leader Spanish Carlos Sainz and Swedish
Kenneth Eriksson, the winner of the latest round in Sweden, were
forced out of rally on Saturday. enditem

