<HEADLINE> Premier Urges Better Application of Science, Technology (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng called for
promoting the application of science and technology to better
benefit economic development in China.
</P>
<P>
"Every year sees the emergence of tens of thousands of
scientific and technological research results in our country, but
those that are genuinely applied in production and converted to a
productive force are a few in number," he said. "That is why, in
future, we must give priority to applying research results in
national economic development."
</P>
<P>
The premier made the call here today at a panel discussion
attended by members of the Eighth National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) who
hail from science and technology circles. The CPPCC National
Committee has been in session since last Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Deng Xiaoping set forth at the National Science Conference in
1978 the scientific thesis that 'science and technology is the
No.1 productive force,'" Li said. "This is a component part of his
theory on building socialism with Chinese characteristics."
</P>
<P>
He said, "We must carry work forward at the behest of Comrade
Deng Xiaoping, unite around the Party Central Committee with
Comrade Jiang Zemin at core, and implement Deng Xiaoping's
thinking on 'science and technology being the No.1 productive
force.'"
</P>
<P>
Citing that Deng Xiaoping as a founder of China's principles
and policies on science and technology, as well as a teacher and
friend of Chinese scientific and technological personnel, Li said
that Deng's tremendous contributions and immortal feats in the
country's socialist modernization drive will be always remembered.
</P>
<P>
Li called on scientists and technicians to implement in an
all-round-way the strategy of relying on science and education to
build up the country, scale the height of science and technology
and go all out to strengthen the work in this regard.
</P>
<P>
An important way to further improve the quality of economic
growth is to rely on scientific and technological progresses, the
premier said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Urges Better Application of Science, Technology (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li Peng emphasized that special attention should be attached to
the application and commercialization of new and high
technologies.
</P>
<P>
"This should be included in economic development plans and
plans for the development of science and technology and given
priority," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for doing a good job in building state high and new
technology development zones and bringing into full play the
initiative of all social quarters, especially industrial
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
On the reform of China's science and technology management
system, the premier held that remarkable results have been made.
</P>
<P>
The orientation for reform in this regard, he said, is "to
gradually move the main force of scientific research and
technological development to enterprises, away from research
institutes, or let research and development proceed simultaneously
in enterprises and research institutes."
</P>
<P>
Li expressed approval for the suggestion that funds for
scientific research and technological development make up 1.5
percent of China's GDP by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"However," he added, "we must change the way investment in this
regard is made. Resources should be used in major areas."
</P>
<P>
The major areas he mentioned are basic research, research for
new and high technologies, and research on key, crucial issues
that have a bearing on natinal economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
The premier thanked Chinese scientists and experts for their
contributions to the country and expressed the hope that they
would air their views freely on his government work report he made
Saturday at the NPC session.
</P>
<P>
During the panel discussion, Vice-Premier Li Lanqing also spoke
on the domestic and world markets and a number of other issues of
concern to the members of the CPPCC National Committee. 
</P>
