<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bee Hatch "Golden Egg" for Farmers Rather Than Honey (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- When people in China talk about
the future development for agriculture, "economy of scale" and
"ecological protection" are, among others, their favorite terms.
</P>
<P>
For Professor Gong Yifei from east China's Fujian province, his
favorite topic is how bees can contribute to the human efforts to
build eco-agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"When bees are busy making honey, their contribution to farm
production is often neglected," ethused the veteran specialist on
apiculture from the Fujian University of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Since bees are the only insect that can be artificially raised,
Gong said, it can be used in helping boost farm production by both
pollinating the flowers and making money.
</P>
<P>
However, Professor Gong added, modern agriculture usually
features the use of large amount of chemical pesticides and
insecticides, which results in the killing of beneficial insects
like bees.
</P>
<P>
When the system of fixing farm output quotas on a household
basis was first introduced in China's rural areas, farmers vied
each other to spray pesticides to boost higher yields on a
short-term basis, but they were soon disappointed as a result of
excessive use chemicals.
</P>
<P>
To his delight, farmers across the country have learned to use
bees they borrowed from bee raisers to work on flowering crops or
fruit trees during the blossom season, which will led to
substantial, high yields.
</P>
<P>
So Prof. Gong warned farmers not to use pesticides during the
blossom season," said Gong.
</P>
<P>
In Professor Gong's hometown of Zhangzhou, a leading Litchi
producer in Fujian province, local governments have in the past
three years issued notices to advise local farmers against the use
of pesticides during blossom seasons since the bees they
introduced can help pollinate the Litchi flowers.
</P>
<P>
"Hence, local farmers have had Litchi harvests for three
consecutive years," said Professor Gong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bees Hatch "Golden Egg" Rather Than Honey for Farmers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhangzhou is not a sole case in point. on large farms in the
western Xinjiang, and in apple tree orchards of the northernmost
province of Heilongjiang, hundreds of millions of bees are used to
raise crop yields.
</P>
<P>
According to Professor Gong, there is no such practice as
borrowing of bees during the period of petty-scale peasant
economy. Since-scale farming was done in many areas, farmers have
become increasingly aware of the aid of bees in the process of
building eco agriculture."
</P>
<P>
And China today has a developed bee keeping business. With some
seven million of bee raising cases, China is the world's top bee
keeping nation.
</P>
<P>
Of tens of millions bee-raising households, a wise and harding
working couple are able to raise 70 or 80 cases of bees, and earn
30,000 to 50,000 yuan annually.
</P>
<P>
"But they have to work hard, and often go deep admist the
forests in mountain areas and hilly regions," the professor said.
</P>
<P>
He himself was a part-time bee keeper some 50 years ago to earn
money for go on schooling.
</P>
<P>
China's first department on apiculture sciences was established
in Fujian Agriculture University in 1960. Professor Gong has be
the dean of this department for decades, and helped to train some
30 bee-keeping specialists every year.
</P>
<P>
After retirement, Gong still works hard and dedicates himself
mainly to bee keeping.
</P>
<P>
The 70-year-old man is rosy cheecked and healthy. When people
asked about his secret, he would said with pride and humorously,
 "I owe my health to bee products and physical exercises as a
bee-keeper." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-communist Leaders Favor Multi-Party Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Three non-communist party leaders
expressed their intention of further consolidating multi-party
cooperation under the leadership of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) to contribute to China's reform, development and stability.
</P>
<P>
The three newly elected non-Communist party chairpersons
are: He Luli, chairperson of the Revolutionary Committee of
the Chinese Kuomintang, Ding Shisun, chairman of China Democratic
League and Chen Siwei, chairman of China Democratic National
Construction Association.
</P>
<P>
The three chairpersons said the system of multi-party
cooperation under the leadership of the Communist Party is a basic
political system in China and conforms to Chinese realities. Under
the system, they said, the CPC is the ruling party holding the
leading position in multi-party cooperation while the
non-Communist parties participate in the running of state affairs
under the leadership of the CPC.
</P>
<P>
Ding Shisun said his party, most of whose members come from
educational circles, pays great attention to education. "Basic
education is the foundation for improving the quality of the
Chinese nation," he said. "Basic education must free itself from
the blind alley of rigid examinations."
</P>
<P>
Ding, who used to be president of China's elite Beijing
University, said higher education plays a dominant role in all
education. In light of the rapid progress in global science and
technology, attention should be paid to strengthening the study of
basic theories and basic training, instead of specialized
training, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ding said his party will carry forward the tradition of
adhering to CPC's leadership and cooperating with the CPC to
contribute more to China's socialist cause.
</P>
<P>
He Luli, in response to a question on the impact of Hong Kong's
return to China on relations between both sides of the Taiwan
Strait, said that Hong Kong's return is an important step forward
toward the reunification of the motherland and, as such, will
surely exert a positive and far-reaching impact on the
international community as well as among Taiwan compatriots.
</P>
<P>
Madame He pointed out that reunification of the country and
reinvigoration of the Chinese nation is the common wish of all
Chinese people, those in Taiwan included. She expressed her
confidence in an early realization of China's reunification.
</P>
</TEXT>
