<HEADLINE> Alphand Wins His Third Downhill Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Luc Alphand captured his third
consecutive World Cup downhill title Sunday while Norway's Lasse
Kjus pleased home crowds by posting his second win of the season
in Kvitfjell of Norway.
</P>
<P>
Kjus clocked a winning time of one minute 27.12 seconds to
claim the downhill victory before the World Cup finals in Vail.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Pietro Vitalini finished second in 1:27.26.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Ed Podivinsky, bronze medalist at the 1994 Olympic
Winter Games, climbed onto the podium for the first time in two
years after placing third, 1:27.56.
</P>
<P>
France's Alphand, who also leads the overall and super-G
standings, will attempt to lockup the super-G title in the
afternoon race.
</P>
<P>
Alphand now has 13 career World Cup wins, including five
downhills and two super-Gs this season. 
</P>
