<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Targets Healthcare Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 800 surgeons from the
Asian region gathered here today to share their insights into how
to cope with increasing costs and expectations in healthcare in a
modern society.
</P>
<P>
The 11th Congress of the Asian Surgical Association opened
today in Hong Kong, a city which hosted the first biennial meeting
20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the congress, Hong Kong
government Secretary of Health and Welfare Mrs. Katherine Fok said
that the rise of aging population and the development of
expensive medical devices have led to a fast-growing healthcare
bill, which has become a serious concern to policy makers and
healthcare professionals in many countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
That was why the current congress focused on how to achieve a
balance between growing needs of patients and growing prices of
healthcare services.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Fok said: "To cope with rising costs, ways have to be
identified to increase the cost-effectiveness of services to be
provided without sacrificing quality."
</P>
<P>
In addition to surgeons from Asia, many distinguished figures
from Australia, Europe and the United States took part in the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
