<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Social Sector Remains Under Great </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Africa's social sector has remained
under great pressure in the 1990s mainly due to cutbacks of public
expenditure on education and health care.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of ''Africa Recovery'' said that the introduction
of user fees for schooling and social services, previously offered
free of charge, has left the poor often without health care and access
to schooling.
</P>
<P>
The publication said the public expenditure in the health sector
rarely exceeded an average of five percent of Gross Domestic Product
(GDP), or 10 US Dollars per capita a year.
</P>
<P>
In many African countries more than 50 percent of the population
has no access to modern health facilities, and 54 percent has no
access to safe drinking water and 66 percent lacks sanitation
services.
</P>
<P>
The impact of poor preventive health care is more severe on
African children, who continue to fall ill or die often from
preventable or treatable afflictions like acute respiratory
infections, diarrhoea, malaria and measles in addition to
protein-energy and micronutrient malnutrition, said the publication.
enditem

