<HEADLINE> Mass Rally for Ex-Gurkhas' Welfare Demands Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Around 10,000 people gathered
here today in a mass rally to show their support for retired
British Gurkha soldiers in Nepal, who have been pressing for
welfare benefits from the British government.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of major political parties in the country attended the
mass rally in an open-air theater in downtown Kathmandu, which was
organized by the Ex-Gurkha Servicemen's Organization.
</P>
<P>
Among the participants of the rally were thousands of
ex-Gurkhas soldiers, who had served in the British Army's Gurkha
Brigade, and their families from across the country.
</P>
<P>
Retired Gurkha soldiers in Nepal started a movement three years
ago to demand equal pensions and facilities as those for their
British counterparts from the British government.
</P>
<P>
The Ex-Gurkha Servicemen's Organization here last year
submitted a memorandum to British Prime Minister John Major
demanding for increased pensions, employment opportunities for
their children and rights to live in Britain.
</P>
<P>
However, the British authorities so far has not given a clear
reply to the welfare demands of the ex-Gurkha soldiers, sources of
the organization said.
</P>
<P>
The British government last month announced a one-million-pound
package program to pay serving Gurkha soldiers same salaries as
their British counterparts and allow their families to accompany
them.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the new measures on serving Gurkhas' treatment,
ex-Gurkha servicemen here urged the British government to make
similar arrangements to solve their welfare problems.
</P>
<P>
There are about 25,000 ex-Gurkhas throughout Nepal, who are
receiving monthly pensions ranging from 30 to 130 US dollars,
according to the British Embassy here.
</P>
<P>
The Gurkha Brigade of the British Army has a 183-year-old
history since Britain began recruiting Nepali youths for its
British Indian Army in early 19th century.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of Nepali soldiers, mostly from northern
Nepal's mountainous areas, had served in the British Army since
then and about 15,000 of them lost their lives during World War I
and II.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
