<HEADLINE> China's Ping'an Second Only to People's Insurance in Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Recent data show that China's
Ping'an Insurance Company has become the country's second largest
insurer, after the state-owned People's Insurance Company of
China, and has 14 percent of the total shares of the domestic
insurance market.
</P>
<P>
According to the company's annual report, it surpassed
Shanghai's Pacific Ocean Insurance Company last year in overall
business and was in second place among the three giant insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
The company has drawn up an ambitious plan to increase sales to
20 billion yuan this year, with business income in life insurance
expected to hit 13 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The company was established in Shenzhen in 1988 and is the
youngest among the three giants, having witnessed the rapid growth
in the business throughout China in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The company's profits last year topped 10.5 billion
yuan. Profits from life insurance alone saw a sharp increase last
year over 1995, reaching 7.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that China's insurance industry will expand quickly
since both of the country's economy and people's annual incomes
have been increasing. Life insurance will be a big slice of
China's insurance pie in coming years, about 100 billion yuan of
which will be generated by profits by the year 2000, experts say.
</P>
<P>
All insurance companies in China have started competing for a
larger share of the market in the country's major cities.
</P>
<P>
In the Beijing Insurance market, Ping'an has controlled 50
percent of the local market for two successive years, generating
one billion yuan in profits last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
