<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Non-Oil Exports Rise Slightly in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's non-oil exports rose
slightly in 1996, "Guardian", a major Nigerian newspaper,
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted privisional figures provided by the Federal
Produce Inspection Service (FPIS) as saying that a total of
362,233.8 tons of various agricutlural products were exported
last year, 4.9 percent up from 1995.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's agricultural exports include cocoa beans, palm
kernal cake, sesane seed, rubber, cashew nuts, coffee, ginger,
palm oil, streanuts, kolanuts and others, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Cocoa continued to be the leading non-oil export of Nigeria,
accounting for 46 percent of the total, or 25 percent up from the
1995 figure, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It, however, noted that the performance of most of the other export
commodities is not so impressive.
</P>
<P>
For example, cashew nuts, the country's next most important
non-oil export after cocoa, recorded a slump of 19 percent from the
18,124 tons of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The export of palm kernel cake rose by 0.1 percent in 1996 to
124,113 tons, but the export of rubber dropped by 49 percent from
1995's 30,600 tons.
</P>
<P>
Other exports such as coffee, ginger and groundnuts all improved
slightly from their respective figures in 1995, but the export of
palm oil, reading three tons in 1995, decreased to none last year,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
It has been the goal of the Nigerian government to promote the
export of its non-oil products, but to date, oil still accounts for 97
percent of the country's export and 83 percent of the government's
budgetary revenue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
