<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethical, Moral Education among Migrating Workers Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Nine members of China's advisory
body have made an official proposal to bolster ethical and moral
education among migrating workers from China's vast rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Led by Xu Weicheng, a Standing Committee member of the Eighth
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), which in its fifth session here, the nine
consultative advisors said that in some cities the relevant
departments have failed to include the ethical and moral education
of migrating workers in their work agenda because they are not
permanent residents.
</P>
<P>
"This is a weak link in building up socialist ethical and
cultural civilization," the members share the view in the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the members recently show that there are
80 million migrating workers across China and 80 percent of them
are rural men and women aged from 18 to 35, with 70 percent only
having a primary or junior middle school education.
</P>
<P>
"Many of them are busy making money, without knowing much about
major national issues and and relevant laws, and some criminals on
the run often sneak into among them," the proposal said.
</P>
<P>
"It is of overriding significance for China to increase ethical
and moral education among this group of people in an effort to
promote socialist ethical and cultural progress," the members said
in the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Easier access to books, newspapers, and radio and television
broadcasting, and other essential conditions should be provided
for these rural-sourced migrating workers, and their children
should be given an opportunity for schooling, the members
suggested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
