<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earliest Image of Monkey King Found in China's Dunhuang Grottos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 2 (Xinhua) -- A fragment of a wall painting in
the Dunhuang Grottos in northwest China's Gansu Province just may
be the earliest image of a well-known figure from an ancient
legend about the Monkey King helping a senior monk bring Buddhist
classics from India.
</P>
<P>
In the painting, the Monk Xuanzang is depicted as putting his
palms together to greet Samantabhadra, the Bodhisattva of
Universal Benevolence, while the Monkey King leads a white horse
behind him by the sea.
</P>
<P>
The painting, which was made some 800 years ago, has finely
depicted hairs on the Monkey King's face, according to Duan
Wenjie, an artist and director of the Institute of Dunhuang.
</P>
<P>
The Dunhuang Grottos, which include the Mogao Grottos, the
Yulin Grottos, and the Ten-thousand Buddha Caves, were built from
the 6th to the 14th century. There are some 2,000 colored statues
and over 40,000 sq.m. of wall paintings there and they are on the
World Heritage List.
</P>
<P>
According to Duan, there are six pictures in the Grottos
depicting the legend, partly because a popular story has it that
local officials helped the monk go westward instead of detaining
him in accordance with imperial verdict when Xuanzang passed the
area in 629.
</P>
<P>
Historical records have shown that it took 10 years for
Xuanzang to walk the distance that it took him to get the Buddhist
classics in India.
</P>
<P>
The first image of the monkey King helping Xuanzang get the
Buddhist classics, according to historical documents, was in
murals at the Shouning Temple in Yangzhou city in 1036, 300 years
earlier than the novel "The Journey to the West" which made the
legend even more popular.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the temple was destroyed and no copies of the
image remain, so "Thus the wall painting in Dunhuang is probably
the oldest extant," Duan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Fertilizer of Poorest Quality: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Fertilizer used in Nigeria is of the
poorest quality in terms of nutrients content in the west African
sub-region, a recent study shows.
</P>
<P>
The research carried out by the International Fertilizer
Development Center-Africa, based in Lome, said that this is likely a
result of poor process control and poorly size-matched raw
materials.
</P>
<P>
The research analyzed fertilizer samples from Benin, Burkina Faso,
Cote d'Ivoire, Ghana, Mali, Nigeria and Togo, and found that 43
percent of them are nutrient deficient.
</P>
<P>
"The percentage of nutrient deficient samples was highest in
Nigeria while it was zero in Benin and Ghana," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The research also found that misbranding and underweighing are two
serious problems in the sub-region. As high as 58 percent of the
sampled bags are underweighed, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It lamented the lack of effective quality control in fertilizer
production, import inspection and distribution and made
recommendations to the authories concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
