<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Medical Care Emphasized by CPPCC Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- College graduates should be
encouraged today to work in rural medical care institutions
to improve medical conditions in China's vast countryside.
</P>
<P>
This suggestion is raised in a proposal submitted to the
Eighth National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) in session now in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made by CPPCC National Committee members from
the Chinese Peasants and Workers Democratic Party, one of the
eight non-communist parties, whose members come mainly from
medical, scientific and educational circles.
</P>
<P>
The central government has decided that rural China is the
focus of development for medical care, the proposal says.
</P>
<P>
The proposal says preferential policies should be formulated to
encourage more graduates from colleges and secondary vocational
schools to work in rural medical institutions.
</P>
<P>
More fund should be pooled for use to improve medical
conditions in poverty-stricken areas, the proposal says. It also
calls for people to donate for these areas for the improvement of
medical conditions.
</P>
<P>
According to the members, poor medical care in the countryside
is a striking problem in today's China. Close to 80 percent of the
Chinese population live in the countryside. Many rural residents
cannot afford to see doctors and some have been stricken by
poverty owing to illness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
