<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy Still to Boom: British Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- A British newspaper said today that
China's economic prospects are still good after the death of
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
"There is no sign anywhere in the collective leadership that
anything will be done to disturb or change the broad thrust of
economic policy begun by Deng," said an article carried in the
Sunday Business.
</P>
<P>
"This will be comforting to the 2,000 or so British companies
who are now doing business in Hong Kong or on the Chinese
mainland, said the article written by Tony Hunt.
</P>
<P>
"Twelve years ago, Beijing had only one five-star hotel and a
lot of rural tenements deep within the city. Today the city has
between 30 and 40 internationally recognized five-star hotels and
the city rocks to a building program that goes on day and night as
the capital struggles to keep pace with a national economic growth
rate of over 9 percent."
</P>
<P>
Hunt suggested that "If you are in business, China is the least
sleep-inducing place on earth."
</P>
<P>
The article also quoted Anthony Russell, a banking analyst at
James Capel, as saying that "Over the last several years China has
jumped from 25th to 10th place in terms of world trade. That is
very significant. But even more significant is China's
determination to expand its share of world trade by one-third,
about 100 billion U.S. dollars, over the next four years. Every
British company should be interested in that."
</P>
<P>
Russell believes more direct investment will have to come from
Europe. "Long-term direct investment will increase Europe's share
of this expansion," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
