<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Absorb "Vigilantes" In Security System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAAM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar President Salmin
Amour has said that "vigilantes", popularly known in Zanzibar as
volunteers, will from now on be part of the government security
units in efforts to strengthen security in the Isles.
</P>
<P>
Addressing "vigilantes" from the three Zanzibar
administrative regions, Amour said in Zanzibar on Saturday that
the move was also aimed at enabling them to work effectively in
maintaining peace and order in the society.
</P>
<P>
He told the "vigilantes" that Zanzibar government would soon
start issuing special allowances to motivate them.
</P>
<P>
The Isles government will also offer military training to
"vigilantes" and give them uniforms.
</P>
<P>
"We are keen at reinforcing the performance of 'vigilantes'",
Amour said, adding that he government appreciated their services.
</P>
<P>
The Isles president also appealed to the people to work together
with "vigilantes" to promote peace and order.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that plans were underway to ease transport problems
facing them, saying the local force had played a major role since its
formation by the then Afro Shirazy Party (ASP) in 1957.
</P>
<P>
The inclusion of "vigilantes" in the government machinery
brings the number of security units in the Isles to four. Others
are the Economic Construction Army, the Reformatory and the
Coastal Secruity Guards. 
</P>
