<HEADLINE> 30,000 Join Charity Walk in HK to Greet Reunification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 30,000 Hong Kong
people took part in three-km charity walk today in celebration of
the reunification of Hong Kong to China within four months' time.
</P>
<P>
The event raised 17 million HK dollars (2.18 million US
dollars), far exceeding the originally expected amount of 10
million HK dollars (1.28 million US dollars), according to Leo Lee
Tung Hai, chairman of the Organizing Committee for the
Celebration of Reunification Charity Walk.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to finance various events of celebration
around July 1, 1997, when China resumes its exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, the first Chief Executive of the future Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) walked with other
participants for 45 minutes along the route stretching from
Charter Garden in the central district to Victoria Park.
</P>
<P>
The first Chief Executive and Zhang Junseng, deputy director of
the Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch officiated the starting
ceremony for the charity walk this morning.
</P>
<P>
The walkathon was jointly organized by the Association of the
Reunification of Hong Kong with China and the Hong Kong Community
Chest.
</P>
<P>
The Charity Walk has so far been held for 120 times in Hong
Kong since the first was launched in 1977. Each year the event
raised a considerable amount of funds to aid more than 700,000
needy persons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
