<HEADLINE> NPC Deputies on Rural Labor Flow (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Legislators attending the Fifth
Session of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) in Beijing
agreed that the government has scored marked progress in
controlling the huge population flow caused by the influx of
job-seeking farmers into cities in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Since the latter half of the 1980s, a large number of rural
surplus laborers from central and western China have poured into
the country's prosperous coastal area to find jobs and make money.
</P>
<P>
This kind of labor flow involves over 80 million people a year.
While helping promote economic prosperity, it has also added
pressure on urban traffic and posed difficulties for city
management.
</P>
<P>
The issue of migrant workers repeatedly appeared in bills
submitted to the past NPC sessions, but this year it is no longer
a hop topic among the legislators.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to the efforts of governments at all levels, the
situation has changed remarkably with a more orderly outflow of
migrant workers from our province," said Deputy Xie Shijie, Party
secretary of southeast China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
As China's most populous province, Sichuan is the country's
number one source of migrant workers, whose number exceeded 6.5
million.
</P>
<P>
Xie, also an expert of agriculture, pointed out that the
problem of migrant population usually turns worst during the
traditional Spring Festival period, when migrant workers going
home for a family reunion exert high pressure on the country's
underdeveloped transportation system.
</P>
<P>
"This year we cooperated with other provinces, and persuaded 60
percent of the migrant workers from Sichuan to stay where they
were during the Spring Festival," Xie said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Deputies on Rural Labor Flow (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Deputies from Guangdong Province in southeast China and
Shanghai in east China said that the local governments have taken
effective measures to ensure the orderly flow of migrant workers,
who have contributed greatly to their local economies.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province, which has a migrant population of over 10
million, in recent years has made every effort to improve its
labor market, and established more than 1,000 employment agencies.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Ye Gongqi, vice chairman of the Standing Committee of
the Municipal People's Congress of Shanghai, said that with over
one million temporary workers from elsewhere, Shanghai has adopted
a series of measures, such as issuance of local work permits and
regular release of employment information, to strengthen the
management of migrant population.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, the local people's congress last year passed
regulations on the management of migrant population, in order to
protect their legal rights and interests," he added.
</P>
<P>
A dozen provinces and municipalities that are major sources of
migrant workers also set up offices in Shanghai to handle labor
affairs, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report delivered at the opening ceremony
of the current NPC session, Premier Li Peng pointed out that a
reasonable and orderly flow of some surplus rural labor to
cities and economically developed regions is the need of economic
development.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the government encourages those farmers
who have become skillful in various fields and who have
gained managerial experience to return to their hometowns to
start new businesses there and to assist in the endeavor to
shake off poverty and become prosperous.
</P>
<P>
While agreeing to the premier's ideas, some deputies said that
the fundamental way to solve the problem of population flow is to
strengthen the economic development in those sources of migrant
workers, especially in poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Peng Fusheng, a local legislator of Chongqing City, pointed out
that it is still an arduous task to achieve a completely
reasonable and orderly flow of rural surplus labor.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 percent of the Chinese population live in
vast rural areas, and official statistics put the size of rural
surplus labor at 130 million. The figure is estimated to rise to
around 200 million by the end of this century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Liberian Warlords Resign for Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Three former Liberian rival warlords,
Charles Taylor, Alhaji Kromah and George Boley, have resigned from the
ruling Council of State, Liberia's interim government, to contest for
the presidency in the general elections scheduled for May this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today, all the three resigned the
post of vice-chairman in the council late on Friday before a February
28 midnight deadline.
</P>
<P>
Their resignation went in compliance with the terms of the peace
accord signed last August in the Nigerian capital of Abuja that
government officials aiming to contest the May 30 polls should quit
their positions.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord was signed by the former rival warring factions to
end the seven-year-old civil war in the West African country, during
which more than 150,000 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
Taylor announced his resignation at a press conference, while
Kromah and Boley made theirs in separate statements on national radio,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Taylor named former Information Minister Victoria Reffell as his
replacement, while Boley and Kromah appointed Weade Wureh and Vamba
Kanneh as respective successors in the Interim Council of State.
</P>
<P>
Until their appointments late on Friday, Kanneh served as Minister
of Health and Social Welfare, while Wureh headed the the Liberia
Repatriation and Resettlement Commission, a government repatriation
agency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
