<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Demonstrate Over Nazi Army Exhibit in Munich </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 2,000 German rightwing
extremists today took to the streets in the southern city of
Munich to protest against an exhibition on atrocities committed by
the German army during World War II, reports said here.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 7,000 left-wing activists held a demonstration
to support the exhibition, which challenges the notion that the
German army had nothing to do with Nazi crimes during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Police said more than 20 right-wing extremists were detained
for portraying outlawed Nazi symbols and three left-wing activists
were seized when trying to attack their opponents.
</P>
<P>
Rallies for and against the exhibition were called after the
exhibition had evoked widespread controversy and emotions in
Munich since the show opened on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition used photographs, diaries and letters from
soldiers themselves to back up its theme that the regular army, as
well as the SS units -- the elite corps of the Nazi party usually
blamed for war crimes, participated in mass killings of Jews and
other atrocities.
</P>
<P>
Some German conservatives said the show was considerably biased
as the German army, called the Wehrmacht in the Nazi era, simply
fulfilled its duty and did not play any role in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
An arch-conservative newspaper accused the exhibit of
"stripping millions of Germans of their honor".
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the exhibition, however, insisted that the
Wehrmacht was involved in war crimes, including the Holocaust,
even though not every ordinary soldier was a criminal.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the show on Monday, Munich's left-wing Social
Democratic (SPD) mayor, Christian Ude, also stressed that Germany
must not have any taboos on historical research and public debate.
</P>
<P>
So far, over 120,000 people from Germany and neighboring
Austria has visited the exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
