<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Large and All-Inclusive, Small and All-Inclusive(21) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Following is an explanation for
the term "large and all-inclusive, small and all-inclusive"
mentioned in Chinese Premier Li Peng's government work report to
the Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Under China's planned economic system in the past, all
localities blindly sought to build an industrial structure that
is inclusive of all products, and all businesses sought to have
the capability to perform all social functions.
</P>
<P>
As a result of this practice, much investment was put into
similar projects and facilities unnecessarily, resulting in a
serious waste of resources and funds.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report, Premier Li Peng suggested that
greater efforts be made to adjust the industrial structure to
solve this long-standing problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
