<HEADLINE> Price Hikes No Longer a Major Concern for Legislators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Price hikes, which used to be a
major concern for Chinese legislators, have stopped being a hot
topic at the ongoing session of the Chinese legislature.
</P>
<P>
This is evident either when legislators spoke at group
discussions or when they expressed views individually in
interviews.
</P>
<P>
Deputies to the National People's Congress (NPC) are here
attending the fifth session of the Eighth NPC.
</P>
<P>
Price hikes were a hot topic in the past few years. Inflation
stood at 13 percent in 1993 and rose to 21.7 percent in 1994
before coming down to 14.8 percent in 1995. Last year it dropped
to 6.1 percent, while the economy continued to surge, to result in
what people call a "successful soft landing."
</P>
<P>
Ding Shisheng, an NPC deputy from northeast China's Jilin
Province, said price control used to be a difficult issue.
</P>
<P>
"It is no easy feat for the government to drive down inflation
without choking economic growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China maintained a growth rate of 9.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Huang Enyuan from Liaoning Province attributed China's
successful economic soft landing to scientific decision-making by
the central government as well as a series of macroeconomic
control and tight financial and monetary policies implemented over
the last few years.
</P>
<P>
Inflation, however, continues to be a major concern for the
Chinese premier, Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report he delivered at the opening
meeting of the NPC session, Li listed a series of measures to
contain price rises. It is a long-term task to rationalize price
relations, requiring both a positive altitude and a reliable
approach, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We should by no means relax control over price rises, as
pressure from inflation still exists and our agriculture is
still weak," said the Chinese premier, who called for continued
implementation of a tight financial and monetary policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
