<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Three Gorges Program  (15) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Following is a brief introduction
to the Three Gorges program, a national key project mentioned in
Chinese Premier Li Peng's government work report to the Fifth
Session of the Eighth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges program highlights China's efforts to harness
the Yangtze river, the world's third longest, which involves the
damming of the river and the building of a vast reservoir along
the gorges.
</P>
<P>
The 57 billion yuan program (calculated according to the 1990
constant price) is aimed at flood control, power generation, and
facilitation of shipping on the river.
</P>
<P>
The super-dam of the program is projected to be 185 meters in
crest elevation. And the hydropower station is designed to be
installed with 26 units with an combined installed capacity of
18.2 million kilowatts and an annual electricity output of 84.7
kw/h, making it the biggest hydropower station in the world. It
will serve as the hub of all the major power grids across China.
</P>
<P>
Resettlement of resident around the area started in October
1992, and the whole project is scheduled to be completed in the
year 2009.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Xiaolangdi Water Control Project (16) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Following is a brief introduction
of the Xiaolangdi Water Control project, a key national project
mentioned in Chinese Premier Li Peng's government work report to
the Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The Xiaolangdi Water Control project is the largest of its kind
on the Yellow River, and is second only to the Three Gorges
program in terms of workload.
</P>
<P>
The project, located 40 km north of the ancient city of Luoyang
in central China's Henan province, will be drained by area of
694,000 sq km, 92.3 percent of the total of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
It aims at prevention of floods and ice run and reduction of
silt deposit. It will also have the functions of water supply,
irrigation and power generation.
</P>
<P>
Its estimated cost is around 40 billion yuan, and there is a
plan to use more than one billion US dollars in overseas-sourced
funds.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the project started in September 1991, and is
due to complete in the year 2001. An international bidding was
held for the main part of the project in July of 1994, and the
price offered by the winner of the bidding was 7.3 billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
