<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 09:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Accepts Partially UN Resolution on Golan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu has promised to the United States that the
UN Resolution 242 would be partially applicable to the Golan
Heights, a newspaper report said today.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the promise at the personal request by U.S.
President Bill Clinton during their White House summit last
month, the English daily The Jerusalem Post quoted Israeli
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu added a proviso to his concession: Israel
must retain its traditional interpretation of Resolution 242,
which calls for Israel's pullout from lands it seized in the
1967 War.
</P>
<P>
Israel's interpretations of the resolution means relinquishing
some but not necessarily all of the territory. In other words,
Netanyahu appeared to be agreeing to the idea of territorial
compromise on the Golan Heights, but not full withdrawal, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Washington last month, Netanyahu said he
would seek a "bridging formula" as a basis for resuming
talks with Syria, but has failed to disclosed what it was
since he returned from the trip.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Netanyahu's position has been that talks with
Syria should begin "without preconditions." The ruling Likud
party has consistently refused to say that Resolution 242
applies directly to the Golan Heights, which Israel captured
from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
Syria has been demanding the talks be resumed from where
they left off last year: Israel should reconfirm the
commitments made by the previous Labor government to the full
withdrawal from Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government led by the slain Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin reportedly agreed to the full pullout from Golan
on condition that adequate security arrangements would be made
to ensure Israel's safety.
</P>
<P>
But the Netanyahu government has turned down Syria's request,
saying it would never recognize the informal understandings
reached between the Labor government and Syria. And former
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher supported the Israeli
position, saying that unsigned statements were not legally
binding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
