<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Neolithic Tribe Site Found in Reservoir Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUOYANG, March 2 (Xinhua) -- A tribe site with a group of tombs
dating back 5,000 years have been found in the construction area
of a reservoir on the Yellow River in central China's Henan
Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists have unearthed 56 of the tombs including
one for a young man wearing a big ivory ring. The tomb, four m by
five m, is the largest neolithic tomb ever found in the country.
</P>
<P>
The experts say that the burial articles found in the tombs
suggest a male-dominating tribe making unique pottery.
</P>
<P>
The buried pottery include tri-pots, jars with a long neck and
pots with a big mouth.
</P>
<P>
To the north of the tomb group located the residential area,
storages and stone tool-making workshops.
</P>
<P>
The site, Zhouli in Mianchi county, is quite different from
nearby sites from the same period in terms of social structure,
the experts say.
</P>
<P>
For instance, they say, people enjoyed more equal social status
in the Xishan city, China's earliest city site ever found.
</P>
<P>
Perhaps it was the uniqueness that made the discovery of the
Zhouli site among China's Top Ten Archaeological Finds last year.
</P>
<P>
The Zhouli site is just one of some 100 tribal sites and tombs
groups from the Late Stone Age (10,000-3,000 years ago) that were
found in the construction area of Xiaolangdi Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
The area, extending some 100 km, will be submerged when the
reservoir is formed. Archaeologists are racing against time to dig
up relics dating from as early as the Peiligang Culture some
7,000-8,000 years ago to the early 1900s in the area to be
submerged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
