<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: System of City Mayors Assuming Responsibility for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
the "Vegetable Basket" (19)
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Following is an explanation for
the system of city mayors assuming responsibility for the
"vegetable basket," a term mentioned in Chinese Premier Li Peng's
government work report delivered at the Fifth Session of the
Eighth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
To ease strains on the supply of vegetables and foodstuffs in
the country, China's Ministry of Agriculture initiated the
so-called "vegetable basket project" in 1988, which aims to:
improve production and marketing of vegetables and foodstuffs,
develop and utilize land resources rationally, adjust the
structure of supply and demand of such products, popularize
production techniques, and improve basic facilities, all for the
purpose of increasing the supplies of vegetables and foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
The central government requires that mayors shoulder the
responsibility of properly filling residents' baskets with
vegetables and foodstuffs, to make a success of the project.
</P>
<P>
From 1988 to 1996, the output of meat, dairy products, eggs,
aquatic products, fruits and vegetables increased remarkably,
helping better the quality of urban people's life.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the average amount of meat, aquatic products,
vegetables and the average number of eggs available for each
Chinese reached or exceeded the world's average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
