<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 09:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Moderates to Form New Political Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 2 (Xinhua) -- A group of moderate liberals
in Kuwait are in their final stages to form a new political
movement in the small Gulf state, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
English daily Arab Times, citing a reliable source, reported
the move, but it did not say when the new political group would be
set up.
</P>
<P>
The source, whose name was not given, said that the new
movement would consist of prominent Kuwaiti businessmen and
intellectuals, and it is currently in the final stage of
"shaping" itself.
</P>
<P>
He said all those aligned to the movement believed that
"the time is right for such a movement to come out and
represent the moderates" in the country.
</P>
<P>
Political parties are banned in Kuwait which has been ruled
by the Sabah Royal family. But more than half a dozen of
political groups representing different walks of life exist and
they are in the forms of various movements and societies.
</P>
<P>
The source said that once the new movement comes into
existence, "it will attract a lot of Kuwaitis who have been
unable to find representation in any of the existing movements
in Kuwait, especially because this movement adheres to
liberalizing the attitude and a free market economy."
</P>
<P>
Since the end of the Gulf War in 1991 when Kuwait was
liberated from the Iraqi occupation, Islamists have dominated the
country's political scene, occupying the majority of Parliamentary
seats in two general elections, the last of which was conducted
last October.
</P>
<P>
The source stressed that the objective of the moderates'
movement was aimed at a representation for those who still
have not found their place in Kuwait's democratic process.
</P>
<P>
He also said the movement did not mean to confront anyone
or anything.
</P>
<P>
However, various fundamentalist Islamic groups in the country
have been a strong opposition force against democratic reform
process, calling for restoration to a thorough implementation of
the Islamic Sharia (law) in various fields of the society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
