<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Transfer Payment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Following is an explanation to
transfer payment, a term mentioned in Premier Li Peng's government
work report to the Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
China's central government was able to transfer part of its
fiscal revenue to grass-root governments following considerable
changes in distribution of fiscal revenues between the central
government and local governments after China introduced the
revenue-sharing system in 1994, hence transfer payment in China.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China's transfer payment includes mainly tax returns
and special fiscal allocations to the grass-root. The new system
is significant in guaranteeing the basic expenditure need of local
governments and in optimizing the distribution of social
resources, improving the industrial structure and ensuring
balanced economic development among all regions.
</P>
<P>
As the central treasury is still plagued by a fairly large
deficit and debt burden, the Chinese government is fiscally
restrained in transferring payments at present.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
