<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China's Tight Fiscal &AMP; Monetary Policies (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Following is an explanation to the
relatively-tight fiscal and monetary policies mentioned in Chinese
Premier Li Peng's government work report to the Fifth Session of
the Eighth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
China began to implement a relatively-tight fiscal and monetary
policy as of the later half of the Eighth Five-Year Plan period
(1991-1995) to curb excessive growth in fiscal expenditures and
total credits and to eventually alleviate inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
Under the relatively-tight fiscal policy, a strict control is
slapped on fixed-asset investment and consumption funds to cut
fiscal deficits. The relatively-tight monetary policy imposes a
squeeze on total credits to reduce the rise in the money supply
below the combination of China's economic growth and inflation
rates.
</P>
<P>
The tight policies have played a significant role in ensuring a
sustained, rapid and healthy development of the Chinese economy,
helping bring down the retail price index to 6.1 percent last year
from 21.7 percent in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
