<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China's Tax Rebate Policy (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Following is an explanation to
China's tax rebate policy, which was mentioned today by Chinese
Premier Li Peng in his government work report to the Fifth Session
of the Eighth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
China first began to pay tax rebates to exporters on a full
scale in April 1985. The policy was fine-tuned in 1988 and 1994,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China's tax rebates to exports
have grown rapidly over the past years, from 1.98 billion yuan in
1985 to 11.3 billion yuan in 1988 and 82.6 billion yuan last year,
which was up 50.5 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
The tax rebate policy has significantly helped to boost China's
foreign trade, which reached 289.9 billion US dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Taxation said last month that China
will not make any major changes to its policy on tax rebates this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
