<HEADLINE> EU Team To Inspect Mwanza Fish Processing Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- A team of experts from the
European Union (EU) is expected to arrive in Tanzania this month to
inspect fish fillet plants in the Lake Victoria Zone, the local
paper "Sunday Observer" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reports said some members of the EU recently imposed a
partial ban on exports of fish fillet from Uganda, as the EU
mission had already inspected 21 fish fillet plants in Uganda,
disqualifying 19 of them from the business.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the 19 fish processing plants, which were said
to produce fish fillets detrimental to human health, had created
fear in the EU market, the reports added.
</P>
<P>
The EU mission would undertake the same task in Kagera, Mara
and Mwanza regions of Tanzania and present its findings to relevant
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Mwanza has eight fish fillet plants so far.
</P>
<P>
Reportedly, Spain, Greece and Italy, all EU members countries,
had imposed a ban on imports of fish fillet from Tanzania
allegedly because they were a health hazard.
</P>
<P>
Reports further said Spain had conducted laboratory examinations
and found that fish fillet produced in Tanzania, Uganda and Kenya
were a health hazard.
</P>
<P>
Following the ban, Tanzania is losing 2,000 million Tanzania
Shillings (about 3.33 million USD) a month from exports of 1,250
tonnes of fish fillet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
