<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: "One Country, Two Systems" (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Following is a brief explanation
for the term "one country, two systems" mentioned in Premier Li
Peng's government work report delivered at the Fifth Session of
the Eighth National People's Congress:
</P>
<P>
The concept of "one country, two systems" was first put forth
by Deng Xiaoping. Since the 3rd plenum of the 11th Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), it has gradually
come to maturity and become a fundamental national policy of
China.
</P>
<P>
It was first proposed for the solution of the Taiwan question.
At a meeting with American visitors in February of 1984, Deng
Xiaoping for the first time used the term "one China, two
systems."
</P>
<P>
He said: "The way we've proposed for the reunification of
Taiwan and the mainland is reasonable. After the reunification,
Taiwan can continue to practice its capitalism, while the mainland
maintains the socialist system. But there must be only one unified
China. This principle can also be applied to the Hong Kong
problem."
</P>
<P>
The report on the work of the government passed by the Second
Session of the Sixth National People's Congress (NPC) in May,
1984, formally used the term "one China, two systems" to summarize
the CPC's principle for the solution of the Taiwan and Hong Kong
questions and the motherland's reunification. Later, the
expression was changed to "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
The Constitution of the People's Republic of China enacted in
1982 stipulates that, if necessary, the state can set up special
administrative regions, whose social systems would be decided by
the NPC through legislation according to specific circumstances.
</P>
<P>
In March of 1992, Jiang Zemin, general-secretary of the CPC
Central Committee, reaffirmed that the principle of "one country,
two systems" is not an expedient measure, but a long-term national
policy that will be unswervingly pursued.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Commitment System for Public Services (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng mentioned the
commitment system for public service sector in his government work
report to the Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's
Congress. Hereby is a brief introduction of this system:
</P>
<P>
Under such a commitment system, institutions with public
service functions should set strict criteria for the content,
standards, and procedures of their service, as well as the
deadline for completing the service and the liabilities.
</P>
<P>
It is also required that the institution set up a supervisory
agency, open a complaint hotline, and punish any employee failing
to fulfill the commitment.
</P>
<P>
The system was first adopted by the construction sector in
Yantai, a coastal city in east China's Shandong Province in June,
1994. After being proved to be very successful, it was introduced
by the Ministry of Construction to the water supply, gas supply,
and public transportation sectors in 36 major cities across the
country in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
In July of 1996, the Publicity Department of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China, and the State Council,
China's cabinet, co-hosted a forum participated by eight principal
ministries and state commissions to promote this system.
</P>
<P>
In November this year, the Ministry of Internal Trade and many
other units in the service sector across the country followed the
example of Yantai and the Ministry of Construction to adopt the
commitment system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
