<HEADLINE> Governor on Guangdong-Hong Kong Cooperation Beyond 1997 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Hong Kong needs the backing of Guangdong and the interior area
in science and technology, while Guangdong needs Hong Kong's
capital and managerial experience," he noted. "That's what I
called 'a new prospect of mutual complementarity and benefits'for
common development."
</P>
<P>
He said that the provincial government of Guangdong will
encourage industrial and commercial sectors of both sides to
strengthen exchange and cooperation that are mutually beneficial,
and will offer various kinds of easy accesses, especially in the
field of public facilities.
</P>
<P>
He went on to list three major advantages of his province in
developing economy.
</P>
<P>
"The Guangdong's gross domestic product accounts for more than
9 percent of the country's total, and the province is adjacent to
Hong Kong and Macao, and also radiative to Southeast Asia," he
said, adding that Guangdong is the ancestry home of approximately
20 million overseas Chinese, who have all been showing attention
to the province's development.
</P>
<P>
Last year, he said, Guangdong's gross national product reached
some 610 billion yuan, 11 percent up from 1995. "Even by
conservative estimate, the economic growth rate for this year will
be maintained at around 10 percent," he predicted.
</P>
<P>
This year, he added, Guangdong will take the concept of
"seeking steady progress and pursuing effective growth" as
guideline, continue to advance a sustained, rapid and sound
development of economy and comprehensive social progress, and
further improve the people's livelihood.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that in 1996, retail sales of social consumer
goods in Guangdong totalled 270 billion yuan, while average
per-capital annual incomes for urban and rural residents reached
7,488 and 3,183 yuan respectively.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the inflation rate in Guangdong was 4.4 percent,
lower than the country's average, and 400,000 most needy in the
province are decently fed and clothed. Net assets of state-owned
enterprises in the province exceeded 260 billion yuan, more than
any other province or municipality in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
