<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor on Guangdong-Hong Kong Cooperation Beyond 1997 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- After its return to the embrace of
the motherland on July 1 this year, Hong Kong will have still
closer ties with its neighboring province of Guangdong, Guangdong
Governor Lu Ruihua said in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a new kind of relationship based on mutual
complementarity and benefits," said Lu, who is attending the
on-going Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's Congress
that started here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the intimate economic and trade ties currently
between Guangdong and Hong Kong, he noted that Hong Kong was the
transit port for 80 percent of Guangdong's imports and exports
last year, which totalled 110 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 80 percent of the investment Guangdong obtained from
overseas since the beginning of reform and opening up in 1979 came
directly or indirectly from Hong Kong, and nearly 80 percent of
the province's overseas-funded enterprises were set up by Hong
Kong businessmen.
</P>
<P>
"Now that the Hong Kong brothers are returning home soon, our
cooperation will develop more smoothly," claimed Lu, who has long
beeen engaged in economic work.
</P>
<P>
Since Guangdong is the ancestral home of most Hong Kong
residents, he explained, people of the two places have similar
customs and lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
"Besides water supply, Guangdong also provides a considerable
volume of vegetables, fruits, eggs, fish, and meat for Hong Kong
market," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that in accordance with the Basic Law of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region, Hong Kong will retain its
capitalist system and lifestyle after 1997, different from the
socialist system practised in Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
"Under the leadership of the central government, however, Hong
Kong and Guangdong will not only maintain their existing economic
ties, but also create still better environment and favorable
conditions to promote such ties," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Guangdong, which is in a period of economic
readjustment, is willing to provide Hong Kong, which is making a
shift in the mode of economic growth, with an opportunity to
transfer its labor-intensive industries to the interior area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
