<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passport Leaking Worries Zambian Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambian passports are the most
prominent and marketable on the South African black market.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Home Affairs Minister Chitalu Sampa in an
interview with ''Sunday Times of Zambia".
</P>
<P>
''We are aware about our passports selling on the black market in
South Africa and we have been in touch with our colleagues in that
country who have promissed to help us track the culprits,'' Sampa
said.
</P>
<P>
Zambians are involved in the racket in which a passport is
believed to be fetching about 460 US Dollars, according to Sampa.
</P>
<P>
Because of the seriousness of the problem, the Zambian High
Commissioner's Office in Pretoria has stopped issuing passports to
Zambians claiming they have lost their passports.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs Deputy Minister Peter Muunga said he was shocked that
passports had continued leaking to foreigners even when officials
from the Anti-Corruption Commission and the Office of the President
were present at the passports offices.
</P>
<P>
Muunga said that some might be leaking from the passports offices
while some Zambians visiting South Africa were selling their
passports and later claiming they had lost them.
</P>
<P>
Last year in Lusaka alone, 59 foreigners of various nationalities
were arrested and prosecuted for illegal possession of Zambian
passports, according to Immigration Public Relations Officer
Catherine Poso, who also said many more had been arrested throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
A senior officer at the passports office said that some of the
passports which were illegally issued had no records at the passports
office. enditem

=03020748

=03020755
NNNN
15:55 15:55 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
