<HEADLINE> Olympic Champion Wins South American Walking Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Jefferson Perez of Ecuador, Olympic
champion of the men's 20-kilometer race walk in Atlanta, chalked
up the crown in the same event at the South American Walking
Championships here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Perez scored the easy victory with a winning time of one hour
26 minutes and 19 seconds, beating the world record holder
Bernardo Segura Rivera of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Perez broke out with three laps remaining and edged the Olympic
bronze medalist Bernardo by four minutes and 12 seconds.
</P>
<P>
However, Viera Galdino took the second at 1:32.18, followed by
his two fellow countrymen Claudio Bortolino and Rodrigo de Araujo,
as Bernardo was not included as a offical participant.
</P>
<P>
A total of 16 atheltes took part in the event held in the
Sports Park here.
</P>
<P>
The victory also gained Perez a berth in the World Cup
tournament slated for April 19 in Prague. 
