<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Gets Ganges Water Less Than Agreed Quantum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh received Ganges water
about 100,000 cusecs less than the quantum mentioned in the water
sharing treaty with India during the last eight day cycle of
February, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh got 200,574 cusecs of water in total from February
21 to 28 as against 312,848 cusecs specified in the accord, which
was signed in New Delhi on December 12 last year, said the
sources.
</P>
<P>
A great volume of 395,402 cusecs of water was available during
the corresponding period in 1996. In comparison to that,
Bangladesh now got 194,828 cusecs lesser quantum of water.
</P>
<P>
Water experts from Bangladesh and India started a joint
monitoring at Hardinge bridge point in Bangladesh on January 15
after the 30-year Indo-Bangladesh water sharing treaty came into
effect on January 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
In the first month of this year, Bangladesh got some 1,817,455
cusecs of water against 2,073,997 received during the same period
of last year when there was no agreement or memorandum of
understanding between the two countries, the sources added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
