<HEADLINE> 15 People Killed in Twisters, Thunderstorms in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen people were killed in
tornadoes and thunderstorms which swept across Arkansas and four
other states today, destroying houses and mobile homes.
</P>
<P>
Four residents were left dead and five trailers crushed by a
twister in the central Arkansas town of Arkadelphia.
</P>
<P>
Arkadelphia Police Chief Bob Johnson was quoted by the
Associated Press as saying that among the 60 mobile homes, there
was only one left standing and "We lost count of the serious
injuries at 19."
</P>
<P>
Six people died and 50 homes were damaged in Little Rock and
surrounding communities. The University Hospital in the city said
dozens of people were treated for injuries.
</P>
<P>
Five people were killed by storms in Mississippi, Kentucky,
West Virginia and Ohio. Ohio also reported that several people
were missing.
</P>
<P>
One person was killed and four others were hospitalized when a
tornado struck Randolph, Mississippi early today, destroying four
homes and damaging nearly a dozen other houses and businesses.
</P>
<P>
By early Saturday afternoon, a record 7.5 inches of rain had
fallen in Louisville, Kentucky, in 24 hours. Rescue workers pulled
people from the roofs of cars stalled in as deep as 6 feet of
water and carried others out of flooded homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
