<HEADLINE> Bulgarian President Visits Hungary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian President Petar
Stoyanov arrived here from Prague today and immediately went into
talks with his Hungarian counterpart, Goncz Arpad.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov showed great interest in Hungary's privatization
drive, infrastructure development and efforts for European
integration, the Hungarian media said.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov, who had visited Poland and the Czech Republic before
coming here, said his country would absorb experience from Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Arpad expressed concern over the difficult situation facing
Bulgaria today.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria saw a government crisis, triggered by prime minister
Zhan Videnov's resignation on December 21, 1996 after months of
criticism for his ill handling of the economy. Strikes and
protests nationwide resulted.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also discussed issues of signing a free
trade agreement as early as possible and strengthening cultural
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov also met with Hungarian Prime Minister Horn Gyula, who
said that Hungary would support Bulgaria in efforts to join the
European Union and the Central Europe Free Trade Zone (CEFTZ).
</P>
<P>
The Warsaw-based CEFTZ was established in 1994 by Poland, the
Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary and Slovenia to eliminate trade
barriers in the region. Romania joined it last month.
</P>
<P>
Gyula said that his country is ready to train for Bulgaria
people specialized in privatization and his government will
consider the possibility of providing food for Bulgaria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
