<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Barters Anti-missile Work for Larger NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia wants to co-develop
theater missile defense capabilities with the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) as a condition for agreeing to the
alliance's expansion plan, a U.S. news report said.
</P>
<P>
The collaboration on some of the alliance's sophisticated
weaponry would be part of "a quid pro quo for Russian
acquiescence" to NATO's enlargement, according to the March 3-9
issue of the weekly magazine Defense News.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was among a list of ideas in four documents
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni Primakov presented to NATO during
his private meeting early this week in Brussels with NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
The magazine quoted NATO and Russian diplomats as saying that
Moscow is looking for political and economic payoffs for agreeing
to NATO's expansion.
</P>
<P>
"Russian officials informally raised the prospect of
cooperating on theater missile defense in private conversations
with NATO officials last summer, and stepped up back-channel
discussions in recent weeks," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The 16-nation military bloc and Russia are negotiating a
charter on their relationship after the alliance expanded into
Central and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Russia, which has seen U.S.-led NATO as a threat to its
security after the dissolution of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact in
1991 and therefore is strongly opposed to the expansion plan,
argues that the future NATO-Russia document should be legally
binding, providing it national security.
</P>
<P>
The charter could include an agreement on industrial
cooperation but is unlikely to address specifically theater
missiles defense, a senior NATO official was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Californian Airport Evacuates Passagers Scared by Toy Gun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- About 1,000 travelers were
evacuated and at least 20 flights were delayed today at the San
Jose International Airport, California, scared by a toy handgun,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Rosemary O'Kane, the airport spokeswoman, said, the evacuation
was caused after airport security reported a handgun in a backpack
brought in the airport.
</P>
<P>
Flights at the San Jose airport, located about 40 miles (64 km)
south of San Francisco, were put on hold for nearly three hours as
airport security searched for the weapon.
</P>
<P>
At last, security officials found that the alleged handgun
was a toy packed in a young boy's carry-on backpack.
</P>
<P>
The incident caused the postponement of at least 20 flights,
interfering with the travel plans of an estimated 4,000
passengers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
