<HEADLINE> Russia Reiterates Opposition to NATO's Expansion Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry stated
today that NATO's eastward expansion would create new dividing
lines in Europe and affect its stability and security.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov's
just-concluded Europe tour, the ministry said that the minister
had meetings and talks in London with British Prime Minister John
Major and Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind to mostly discuss NATO
expansion to the East and relations between Russia and NATO, as
well as a binding document between them.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in London, the last leg of the Russian
foreign minister's week-long trip, Primakov expressed satisfaction
with his trip to four European countries, describing it as
"positive and constructive."
</P>
<P>
Primakov meanwhile reiterated Moscow's opposition to NATO's
eastward enlargement plans and warned that "there were some things
to which Russia cannot agree, including the movement of NATO's
military infrastructure to the Russian border."
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency quoted diplomatic sources in the
Russian delegation as saying that if NATO disagreed with
compromise on issues concerning Russian's security, Moscow may
have to sever its relations with the alliance, shift its foreign
policy focus to bilateral ties and change its diplomatic
priorities.
</P>
<P>
However, the sources said, Russia will exert all its efforts to
make NATO compromise on the new European security architecture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
