<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Urged to Make Joint Efforts in Seeking Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has urged Southeast Asian countries to work as a group to
increase their bargaining power in fund seeking and strengthen
their muscles in crisis prevention.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by IMF managing director Michel Camdessus
when finance ministers from the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) held their first meeting in southern Thailand's
Phuket province on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus wanted to see ASEAN members to form a group with its
own financial scheme to help some members solve their financial
problems before resorting to the IMF, according to local
newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus cited the example of the Mexico financial crisis
where the IMF was able to extend assistance because the other two
members of the North America Free Trade Agreement -- the United
States and Canada -- had extended help.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN should create a mechanism similar to the IMF's new
arrangement to borrow scheme in which emergency credit of up to 48
billion US dollars has been available to its 25 members to
overcome financial problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
After succeeding in creating a free trade area, Camdessus said,
ASEAN countries should embark on a new area of cooperation by
making contributions to help member countries fight financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
For instance, ASEAN countries might agree not to withdraw the
fund from a particular country which is facing financial turmoil
for a certain period, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chatu Mongol Sonakul, permanent secretary of the Thai Finance
Ministry, said that just one ASEAN member would be quite difficult
to obtain any financial assistance from the IMF since the approval
is subject to the representatives of 180 members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans Further Deficit Cut: Minister (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- China this year will continue to
follow an appropriately tight fiscal policy and take further
measures to reduce its deficit, according to Minister of Finance
Liu Zhongli.
</P>
<P>
"We should... continue to follow a relatively stringent
financial policy, promote readjustment and optimization of the
economic structure, tighten the collection and administration of
taxation in an all-round way," Liu said in a report to the Fifth
Session of the Eighth National People's Congress, China's
legislature that opened its annual meeting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Liu proclaimed success in cutting deficit to 61 billion yuan by
the end of last year, which was 442 million yuan less than the
budgeted figure.
</P>
<P>
This year efforts will be made to ensure rapid growth in
revenue, control total expenditures and keep the increase in
expenditures below that in revenue, in order to further cut the
deficit and control the debt scale, he said.
</P>
<P>
China's state revenue this year is budgeted at 839.794 billion
yuan, up 14 percent over the actual figure for 1996, while total
expenditures are expected to grow 13.3 percent from the actual
figure for 1996 to 896.794 billion yuan, according to Liu.
</P>
<P>
He said that revenue in the central budget is planned at
475.384 billion yuan, 50.0158 billion yuan more than the actual
figure for 1996, or an increase of 11.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Expenditures in the central budget will total 532.384 billion
yuan in 1997, 46.158 billion yuan more than the actual figure for
last year, or a rise of 9.5 percent, Liu told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"When the revenue and expenditures in the central budget are
compared, there will leave a deficit of 57 billion yuan, four
billion yuan less than the actual figure for 1996," the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that expenditures in the central budget will rise
by four billion yuan as China needs to increase grain and cotton
reserves.
</P>
<P>
Another 2.5 billion yuan is needed to increase funding for
poverty relief and for transfer payment to areas inhabited by
ethnic groups and poverty-stricken areas, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Hong Kong's return to the motherland and a
planned wage rise for employees of administrative departments and
institutions will also increase expenditures in the central
finance.
</P>
<P>
"Even under these circumstances, the central budget deficit is
expected to reduce by four billion yuan as compared with the
figure for 1996," Liu noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese government's Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000), China will have basically eradicated fiscal deficit
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that China plans to issue 248.596
billion yuan in treasury bonds this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Commercial Banks to Build More Branches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- China's new commercial banks will
create more branches in 1997 to further expand their business in
prosperous regions and major economic centers.
</P>
<P>
Their major battlefields will be in the areas such as the
Yangtze River Delta and Pearl River Delta, and big cities like
Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, reported China Daily's Business
Weekly today.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Pudong Development Bank, whose business was originally
limited to the provinces along the Yangtze River, received
approval to build a Beijing branch last year. Now it is preparing
for a Chongqing branch.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Development Bank, which had focused its business
in Shenzhen, set up a branch in Hainan Province and several more
in other cities in Guangdong Province. A Beijing branch is planned
for 1997.
</P>
<P>
There are 12 new commercial banks, including the expanding
regional banks and others designed to be national lending
institutions.
</P>
<P>
They were created after 1986 to compete with China's four
State-owned specialized banks -- the Industrial and Commercial
Bank of China, the China construction Bank, Bank of China, and the
Agricultural Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
China's all-round financial reform required the "Big Four" to
transform into genuine commercial banks after 1994, putting the
four old-timers on the same performing stage with their fresh
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of the new banks coincided with the four big
banks' withdrawal from areas in which business was slow.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Dai Xianglong said about 1,000 affiliates
of the "Big Four" were closed during the past year and officials
of the four banks said the move will continue in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
