<HEADLINE> Brazil's GDP to Grow by 3.9 Percent in 1st Semester </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Brazilia's gross domestic
product (GDP) will grow by 3.9 percent during the first semester of
this year compared with the same period of 1996, according to
offical estimates.
</P>
<P>
Recent forecasts from the Applied Economy Research Institute
(IPEA) show industry will grow by 4.9 percent during the first six
months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit in 1997 is estimated at 7.5 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The GDP increased by 3.1 percent last year, compared with 4.2
percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian economy has grown in recent years between 3 and 5
percent, and inflation dropped to 10 percent in 1996 from 1,320
percent in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
