<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Farmers Urged to Boost Paddy Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Senior-General Than
Shwe today urged farmers in the country to strive for boosting
production of paddy and other crops for both local sufficiency and
export.
</P>
<P>
In his message marking the 1997 Myanmar Peasants' Day which
falls on today, Than Shwe, chairman of the State Law and Order
Restoration Council (SLORC), stressed the government is giving
priority to the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
He said that efforts are being made to achieve 20 million tons
of paddy output annually, cultivating paddy on 6.48 million
hectares with the aims for local sufficiency of rice keeping with
population growth of the country and boosting export of paddy.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that during the previous four-year plan period
(from 1992-93 to 1995-96), the annual paddy output was recorded at
17 million tons, the maximum, and 14 million tons, the minimum.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is implementing plans for expansion of
cultivation areas and boosting per-hectare yield and multiple
cropping to realize the targeted paddy output.
</P>
<P>
The government is also carrying out plans for local sufficiency
of edible oil within three years starting from the 1995-96 fiscal
year and making efforts for expansion of edible oil crop
cultivation area and boosting per-hectare yield, he said.
</P>
<P>
Encouragement and support are also being provided for extensive
cultivation of beans for export and industrial crops such as
cotton, sugar-cane, jute, rubber, coffee and mulberry, he added.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that 75 dams have been built since 1988 when the
SLORC came to power, irrigating over 405,000 hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
The Senior-General called for mechanization systems for the
progress of agriculture and use of fertilizers to boost the output
of crops.  
</P>
</TEXT>
