<HEADLINE> ASEAN Ministers Pledge Greater Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 2 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN finance ministers promised
greater economic integration and closer cooperation of their
monetary and fiscal policy management at their one day meeting
Saturday in Phuket, southern Thailand, according to a report
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to provide preparations for the ASEAN
Free Trade Area (AFTA) which will take effect in 2003.
</P>
<P>
The results of the discussions will be submitted to an ASEAN
leaders conference that will be held in Kuala Lumpur at the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The ministers reaffirmed commitment to further liberalization
of financial service sectors as part of the deregulation and
liberalization process.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN finance ministers agreed to meet on an annual basis and
also to provide a framework to increase cooperation in finance
areas, including banking sector, capital market, customs and
insurance matters, taxation and human resource development.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers signed the ministerial understanding on
ASEAN cooperation during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Thai Finance Minister Amnuay Viravan was quoted as saying that
the ministers agreed that regular consultation will create better
understanding of each country's economic management. The ministers
hoped to broaden and deepen their cooperation in banking among the
region.
</P>
<P>
They also signed the ASEAN agreement on customs which aims to
eliminate some trade barriers among members.
</P>
<P>
Such cooperation should come in the form of joint efforts over
areas such as anti-smuggling, mutual technical assistance and the
upgrade of customs skills and procedures.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation is expected to facilitate trade and investment
among the region, said Amnuay.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed on a further enhancement of ASEAN
cooperation in insurance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. "Decertification" Not Affecting Economy, Says Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's economy has
not been affected by the U.S. "certification" denial of the
country's efforts against drugs, the National Exporters
Association of Colombia (Analdex) said today.
</P>
<P>
Analdex said during the first 11 months of 1996 the export
volume in the country reached 3.7 billion U.S. dollars, a 26
percent increase over 1995, while imports hit 4.803 billion
dollars, up 3.9 percent over the same period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
On March 1 last year, U.S. President Bill Clinton suspended
most U.S. aid to Colombia after concluding that the Colombian
government had failed to cooperate with the U.S. in the war on
drugs.
</P>
<P>
There were no losses of tariff preferences and no increase in
customs taxes, it said. Credits to the country continued to be
granted, though the pace of investments did not quicken, Analdex
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
