<HEADLINE> Albanian Government Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian government led by
Prime Minister Aleksander Mexsi resigned today, as the political
crisis intrigued by the failure of a nation-wide savings scheme
in January worsened.
</P>
<P>
President Sali Berisha accepted Mexsi's resignation after
emergency talks with leaders of the parties in the coalition
government and the country's largest opposition -- the Socialist
Party.
</P>
<P>
Berisha told the state television that the leaders of the
political parties came to conclusion that the Meksi government
must resign in the current situation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Berisha asked Meksi to stay on as caretaker until a
new prime minister is named following consultations with other
political parties.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party, which holds almost all the seats in
parliament after polls last year, would still be in the central
position of the new cabinet, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Democratic Party must consult other political
forces in the formation of the new government, he added.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Berisha also proposed to set up a committee
made up of experts from all political parties, to investigate into
the collapse of the savings scheme.
</P>
<P>
The committee would propose to the new government on how to
solve the economic problems of the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Albania has been racked by anti-government protests since
controversial "get-rich-quick" pyramid investment schemes began to
collapse in January.
</P>
<P>
Protests and Violences swepted through the country since
January, which was highlighted by an armed clash in the southern
port city of Vlore at the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
At least nine persons were killed and 20 others injured during
the clash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
