<HEADLINE> China's Auto Makers to Reshuffle into Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- China's top 20 auto makers will
reshuffle into three or four enterprise groups by the turn of the
century to meet overseas competition.
</P>
<P>
According to the "Business Weekly", several of China's top auto
makers are poised to acquire smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
One-hundred-sixteen car-makers are registered with the Ministry
of Machine-Building Industry which oversees the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
The urgency to develop competitive groups is mounting as China
begins new negotiations to enter the World Trade Organization
(WTO). Automobiles are expected to be among the key issues in the
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
To accelerate the reshuffling process, the ministry will
consider pressuring 30 small, money-losing plants to seek help
from big enterprises or file bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
China has taken effective measures for a better industrial mix
for the past six years. Seventy-eight per cent of the 59 billion
yuan investment in 1991-95 went to top 33 auto plants.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the top 10 enterprise groups produced 80 per cent
of China's automotive output last year, or 1.49 million vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Investment for 1996-2000, expected to be 146.7 billion yuan, is
mostly for big, promising enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Most world auto makers are engaged in ambitious globalization
programs, making the world's production capacity exceed demand by
10 million vehicles. By 2000, the glut will amplify to 20 million,
the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
