<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frei Returns From US Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Chilean President Eduardo Frei,
who returned home on Saturday from the United States, said here
today that his five-day U.S. visit opened a new chapter in
bilateral commercial and political ties.
</P>
<P>
"The trip has been tremendously important for Chile," he told
the press, saying he was quite satisfied.
</P>
<P>
Chile wants to enter the North American Free Trade Agreement
(NAFTA), which has been operating among the United States, Mexico,
and Canada since January, 1994.
</P>
<P>
The president said he presented the reality of Chile "without
hiding anything, showing our small advances and shortcomings."
</P>
<P>
President Frei reiterated that Chile did not go to ask anything
from the U.S. people, but rather to present the country's attitude
about political and economic themes, which were discussed during
the visit.
</P>
<P>
He said President Bill Clinton's administration would request,
as a result of the visit, U.S. Congress authorization to negotiate
"on the fast track" the insertion of Chile into the NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
Frei told the United States during his visit that White House
lack of consensus with the U.S. Congress to define the terms of a
free trade agreement with his country would force Chile to seek
forging accords with Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean president made it clear that Chile opposes to the
Helms-Burton law, imposed by the U.S. last year aiming to blockade
Cuba, and any restricting conditions for free trade in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that delays in the implementation of free trade in
Latin America mean "the weakening of many democracies, the rebirth
of captive markets, the consolidation of hunger and migrations."
</P>
<P>
Frei and Clinton also discussed matters of common interest,
such as the second Summit of the Americas to be held here next
March.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed three agreements during Frei's visit,
including one about new airline schedules between Chile and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Under another of the agreements, a new bilateral commission
will be created for educational communications and cooperation
between the National Library of Chile and the U.S. Congress
migrations."
</P>
<P>
"El Mercurio," the Chilean daily with the biggest circulation
in the country, described today Frei's U.S. trip as "a sober and
eloquent presentation in a visit that had a great stature and
dignity."
</P>
<P>
Among his 130 entourage were Jose Miguel Insulza, Minister of
Foreign Relations, Alvaro Garcia, Minister of Economy as well as
top business executives.
</P>
<P>
The United States is Chile's biggest trade partner, with a
bilateral commercial exchange that surpassed 6 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996, and the first source of foreign investments
in Chile, with a total of 8,579.7 million dollars invested between
1974 and 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
