<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Budgets Well Implemented: Minister (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Minister of Finance Liu Zhongli
said here today that China's moderately tight fiscal policy was
successful last year and that both the central and local budgets
were well implemented.
</P>
<P>
State revenue outgrew expenditures by 18 percent to 16 percent
last year and the fiscal deficit was below the budgeted figure,
Liu told the Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's
Congress, which opened here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The growth of China's state revenue exceeded that of
expenditures for the first time in 1994, by a margin of one
percentage point.
</P>
<P>
Last year state revenue came to 736.661 billion yuan, 107.2
percent of the budgeted figure, or up 18 percent over the 1995
figure, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Total state expenditures reached 791.438 billion yuan in 1996,
105.7 percent of the budgeted figure, or an increase of 16 percent
over 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu, China's revenue in the central budget
amounted to 425.226 billion yuan in 1996, or 101.7 percent of the
budgeted figure.
</P>
<P>
Total expenditures in the central budget reached 486.226
billion yuan in 1996, or 101.4 percent of the budgeted figure.
</P>
<P>
"Central expenditures exceeded revenues by 61 billion yuan, 442
million yuan less than the budgeted amount," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, fiscal revenue increased by a big margin, and the
trend of its proportional shrinkage in the gross domestic product
was brought under control, he noted. Also brought under control
were total expenditures, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have attained our objective of reducing deficit in the
central budget," he said. "This shows that the relatively
stringent financial policy was carried out fairly satisfactorily."
</P>
<P>
However, financial difficulties and potential risks still
exist, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the deficit is still large, the central finance
still relies too much on debts, tax losses are still great,
financial and economic disorder is not yet rectified
fundamentally, and the unauthorized establishment of funds and the
collection of arbitrary charges are still common. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
