<HEADLINE> Argentine Economy Grows in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem said today that his country's gross domestic product (GDP)
grew by 4.4 percent to 300 billion U.S. dollars in 1996 after two
years of recession.
</P>
<P>
Menem told a Congress session that Argentina's per capita
income amounts to nearly 9,000 dollars in 1996, the highest in
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade recorded a 16 percent increase during the
1995-1996 period, with exports and imports growing by 14 and 18
percent respectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the field of foreign investment, 309 projects were
registered in the period from 1994 to the beginning of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The president attributed the previous economic recession to
external crisis and expected a reduced unemployment in the
economic revival.
</P>
<P>
The government will pay special attention this year to public
and private investment in the construction and infrastructure
sectors and creating more jobs, he said. 
</P>
