<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Market stronger than Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- After experiencing a technical
correction the previous week, the Shenzhen market performed
stronger than Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
A report, published by China Daily's Business Weekly today,
concludes that the Shenzhen market has outshined Shanghai over the
past week after comparing the ups and downs in the two markets.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai market continued to climb last week with the index
rising 23.14 points to close at 1,040.27, while the index of the
Shenzhen market climbed 187.34 to end the week at 3,769.55, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai market dropped moderately on Monday when some
investors began to sell shares to profit from the continuous rise
the last three days of the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The market gradually picked up the next two days as investors
believed the market would stand above 1,000.
</P>
<P>
Transaction value was 32 billion yuan (3.8 billion US dollars),
two billion yuan (361.4 million US dollars) less than the previous
week.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai B-share index continued to rise the first three
days of last week because of institutional speculation in selected
stocks.
</P>
<P>
Market sentiment improved after a securities official on
Thursday said he was confident of the B-share market development.
Most investors believe the market will receive more government
support.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied on thursday and Friday, closing last week at
67.15 points, 1.58 higher than the previous week's ending.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen's A-share market extended the previous Friday's gains
to the first three days last week, with the index rising 179
points.
</P>
<P>
After dipping 1.84 points on Thursday, the market rose again on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Market sentiment was stable, reflecting investors' confidence
in China's future after veteran Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping's
death.
</P>
<P>
Most investors showed optimism over the market's medium-term
outlook, given the stability of China's economic and political
environment, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
Some brokers said shares faced a moderate correction on
anticipation of profit-taking after their recent steady rises.
They said technical charts showed signs of over-buying.
</P>
<P>
But they said there was a slim chance of a sharp decline soon.
</P>
<P>
Transaction value was 42 billion yuan (five billion US
dollars), three billion yuan (361.4 million US dollars) more than
the previous week.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen's B-share index closed slightly lower on Monday on a
technical correction after continuous rises the past few trading
days.
</P>
<P>
But the market rose again the next four days to close at
1,344.57 points, 33.84 higher than the previous week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
