<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good Economic Performance for 1996  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Chen Jinhua, minister in charge of
the State Planning Commission, said China's 1996 plan was carried
out satisfactorily, marking a good beginning in implementing the
Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
Chen made the announcement when he made a report on the
implementation of the 1996 Plan for National Economic and Social
Development and on the Draft 1997 Plan for National Economic and
Social Development at the ongoing fifth session of the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC), which opened on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Chen said, China achieved a sustained, rapid economic
growth and the government successfully curbed inflation.
</P>
<P>
Retail prices rose by 6.1 percent, much lower than the 10
percent or so projected in the state plan and a drop of more than
eight percentage points from the previous year; gross domestic
product reached 6,779.5 billion yuan, an increase of 9.7 percent,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"This means China has kept the rate of price rises lower than
the rate of economic growth in accordance with the Ninth Five-Year
Plan," he said.
</P>
<P>
The production of most major manufactured products reached or
exceeded targets set in the state plan. Among them, national
primary energy production reached 1.26 billion tons of standard
coal, 106.2 percent of the planned figure; electricity, 1,075
billion kwh, 100.5 percent of the planned figure; steel, 101.1
million tons, 105.3 percent of the planned figure.
</P>
<P>
Other major statistics he mentioned include: ethylene, 3.01
million tons, 118 percent of the planned figure; chemical
fertilizers (calculated on the basis of active ingredients), 26.6
million tons, 108.8 percent of the planned figure; chemical
fibres, 3.08 million tons, 106.2 percent of the planned figure;
digitalized telephone switches, 19.34 million lines, 101.8 percent
of the planned figure.
</P>
<P>
Chen said China's total grain output exceeded 480 billion kg,
an increase of more than 13.4 billion kg over the previous year.
It was a historical record. Outputs of oil-bearing crops and
cotton went down slightly. They were 22 million tons and 4.2
million tons respectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said investment in fixed assets continued to grow
and the construction of key state projects was strengthened.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,366 billion yuan was invested in fixed assets in
1996, an increase of 18.2 percent over 1995 and representing an
investment rate of 34.9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Kills 13 Detainees in Armenia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 1 (Xinhua) -- A fire broke out today in a police
department in Idzhevan, northeastern Armenia, killing 13 people
locked in detention, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Police forgot to unlock the cell doors in their hurry to escape
the fire, which destroyed the police department in the small town,
the news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It said the fire was caused by a short-circuit of the power
cable.
</P>
<P>
Competent authorities sent 10 fire engines to extinguish the
fire, the news agency said, adding that four policemen were
seriously injured and hospitalized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good Economic Performance for 1996 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Efforts to restructure investment were intensified, with the
growth rate of investment in agriculture, forestry, water
conservancy, energy, transportation, communications and the
electronics industry higher than the overall investment growth
rate, he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, China also accelerated construction of key state
capital construction projects and major technological upgrading
projects. The number of large and medium-sized capital
construction projects completed and put into operation totaled
134, exceeding the target of 97 planned at the beginning of 1996
and hitting an all-time high in this regard in recent years.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, China's national revenue grew
rapidly and the financial situation remained stable. In 1996,
national revenue (excluding revenue arising from loans) totaled
736.6 billion yuan, an increase of 18 percent over the previous
year, and expenditures (excluding repayment of loans), 791.4
billion yuan, an increase of 16 percent, leaving a deficit of 54.8
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The deficit for the Central Government was 61 billion yuan,
which was smaller than the budgeted figure, while local
governments had a surplus of 6.2 billion yuan, he said.
</P>
<P>
The pace of reform of state enterprises was quickened and
supporting reforms continued to deepen. The experiment to
establish a modern enterprise system is in full swing. The number
of cities optimizing the capital structure on a trial basis
increased from 18 to 58.
</P>
<P>
There was a sustained growth in foreign trade and more foreign
capital was used. In 1996 imports and exports totaled 289.9
billion US dollars, an increase of 3.2 percent over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
To break up, exports were valued at 151.1 billion US dollars,
an increase of 1.5 percent, and imports, 138.8 billion US dollars,
up 5.1 percent, leaving a trade surplus of 12.3 billion US
dollars. Foreign investment amounted to 42.35 billion US dollars,
an increase of 12.2 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Fresh progress was registered in science, technology and
education and all social undertakings. In 1996 the average per
capita net income of rural people reached 1,926 yuan, representing
an actual increase of nine percent over the previous year. Urban
dwellers' per capita income available for living expenses amounted
to 4,377 yuan, an actual rise of 3.3 percent, Chen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Focus on Eight Tasks for 1997  (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- China will concentrate on eight
aspects of economic life as major tasks for economic and social
development in 1997, said Chen Jinhua, minister in charge of the
State Planning Commission, today.
</P>
<P>
The eight tasks include: strengthening agriculture,
reinvigorating state-owned enterprises, optimizing the investment
structure, scaling down prices rises, making better use of foreign
funds, maintaining financial stability, developing science,
technology and education and improving the living standard.
</P>
<P>
In his report on the implementation of the 1996 Plan for
National Economic and Social Development and on the Draft 1997
Plan for National Economic and Social Development delivered at the
annual session of NPC, Chen said the goals for the year 1997 runs
as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- The economy should grow by eight percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Retail price rises should be confined to six percent
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
-- The rate of investment in fixed assets should reach 32
percent.
</P>
<P>
-- The deficit should be diminished by four billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
-- Total imports and exports should reach 310 billion US
dollars, with a rough balance between imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
-- Total volume of currency to be issued should be 120 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
-- The natural population growth rate should be confined to
1.144 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- The registered unemployment rate should be about three
percent.
</P>
<P>
To achieve above goals, he said China will continue to give
agriculture the first position in our economic work and ensure a
steady increase in the production of major agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, in 1997, he said the area sown to
grain crops will be maintained at 1.68 billion mu (about 110
million hectares). Gross grain output should remain at the 1996
level, but efforts should be made to exceed this level if
possible, with the emphasis on working to increase wheat and rice
output.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Focus on Eight Tasks for 1997  (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Besides, China will strive to bring the area sown to cotton
back to 80 million mu (530,000 hectares) for a total cotton output
of 4.25 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the 10.8 billion yuan earmarked for construction
as a form of relief funds, anti-poverty loans and development
funds for underdeveloped areas, the Chinese Government will grant
poverty-stricken areas another 1.5 billion yuan in anti-poverty
funds and three billion yuan in anti-poverty loans to improve the
basic production and living conditions there, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister told people at present the Chinese government will
give priority to the reinvigoration of state enterprises and shift
the focus in industrial production to restructuring and improved
economic performance.
</P>
<P>
The Central government will target added industrial value in
the 1997 plan for an increase of 11.5 percent. The output of major
products he mentioned are: coal, 1.37 billion tons; crude oil,
153.5 million tons; electricity, 1,145 billion kwh; steel, 100
million tons; chemical fertilizers (calculated on the basis of
active ingredients), 26.6 million tons; chemical fibres, 3.1
million tons; automobiles, 1.6 million; ethylene, 3.5 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, total fixed asset investment in the country will be
2,530 billion yuan, 1,807 billion yuan of which will go to state
enterprises and institutions.
</P>
<P>
In distributing newly added budgetary investments and bank
loans, Chen said the Chinese government will give priority to
agriculture, water conservancy, energy, communications, national
defence and industries using high and new technologies as well as
science, education, culture and other projects to improve
socialist culture and ideology.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1997 plan, 83 large and medium-sized key
projects will be completed and put into operation and the
construction of a number of key projects will enter the crucial
stage.
</P>
<P>
In his report, he said interception of the Yangtze River for
the Three Gorges Project and damming of the Yellow River for the
Xiaolangdi Project, both major water conservancy projects, are
planned to be completed in 1997. The track-laying of the
Nanning-Kunming Railway should be completed.
</P>
<P>
China will further bring down price rises and consolidate and
develop our achievements in working to curb inflation during the
past three years and focus on improving performance, quality and
reputation to expand foreign trade, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Focus on Eight Tasks for 1997 (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On opening up of markets, Chen said China will strive to open
new markets, especially markets in the Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS), East Europe, Latin America, Southeast Asia and
Africa. Efforts will also be made to increase export credit to
support the export of complete assemblies of equipment.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to make vigorous, but rational and
effective, use of foreign funds to ensure good returns. Foreigners
should be encouraged to invest in general agricultural
development, infrastructure, comprehensive use of resources and
high and new technologies, as well as in projects in the central
and western regions, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to implement an appropriately stringent
financial policy, increase revenue and reduce expenditures and
keep the deficit within the targets set for macro-economic control
so as to maintain a stable financial stability, he continued.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the development in science, technology, education
and all social undertakings, he said, China will improve the
technical processing of scientific and technological advances, and
vigorously work for the translation of these advances into
productive forces. China will also continue to make nine-year
compulsory education more widely available, concentrating on
eliminating illiteracy among young and middle-aged people.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1997 plan, schools throughout the country will
enroll 61,000 postgraduates, 1.01 million undergraduates in basic
and special courses.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China will also develop culture, radio, TV, films,
the press, publishing, sports and public health. Radio coverage
should reach 84.2 percent and TV coverage, 87.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1997,the amount of per-capita income available for living
expenses for city dwellers and the average per capita net income
of the rural population should each increase by about five
percent, he noted. The retail sales of consumer goods in the whole
country should reach 2,870 billion yuan, an increase of 16.7 per
cent over last year. The pace of launching reemployment projects
should be quickend in order to find employment for those who have
lost their jobs, and some 5.5 million new jobs should be created
in urban areas in 1997, Chen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
