<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Intensify Restructuring Efforts: Minister (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- China will intensify restructuring
and improve quality of growth and performance of national economy,
said Chen Jinhua, minister in charge of the State Planning
Commission today.
</P>
<P>
In his report on the Implementation of the 1996 Plan for
National Economy and Social Development and on the Draft 1997 Plan
for National Economic and Social Development, Chen said China will
continue to strictly control the startup of new projects.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government will also screen projects which
have been approved but not yet launched. "We should be firm in
cancelling approval for construction of redundant projects which
would add to the already excessive production capacity in the
country and construction of projects without sufficient funding,"
he told the NPC deputies.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the government will strive to solve
such economic problems as having enterprises, whether large or
small, operating as self-contained units, and reckless and
redundant construction.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will also be made to meet market demand and cultivating
new economic growth areas.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Chinese government will accelerate the
development of industries and products which are in great demand
in the market, call for a high degree of association among
industries, are technologically advanced and show good economic
performance.
</P>
<P>
Industries using high and new technologies such as
electronically-transmitted information and urban housing
construction could be important growth areas for the whole
country.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, China will should work vigorously to
explore the rural market and promote the development of related
industries.
</P>
<P>
In his report, he considered electronics and information
industries a new area of economic growth and an important means
for transforming traditional industries and improving and
upgrading the industrial structure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slaney Scores Year's Best Mark in Women's 1,500 Meters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Mary Slaney scored the year's
best mark in the women's 1,500 meters at the U.S. Indoor Athletics
Championships at Atlanta on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Competing for the first time in the U.S. Indoor Championships
in 23 years, Slaney clocked 4 minutes 3.08 seconds to take the
title. The results was the best since Doina Melinte of Romania
set the world record of 4:00.27.
</P>
<P>
Slaney, American indoor records holder at 800 meters, 880
yards, 1,000 meters, 1,500 meters and the mile, was never
seriously challenged after she surged to the front.
</P>
<P>
She beat runner-up Suzy Hamilton by nearly 40 meters.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 600 meters dash, two-time Olympic champion Gail
Devers beat Olympic bronze medalist Gwen Torrence. Devers'
winning time of 7 seconds also stands as the year's best. 
</P>
</TEXT>
