<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian's Forest Coverage Top of List in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The forest coverage rate of east
China's Fujian Province has reached 57.3 percent, the highest in
China, according to provincial government statistics.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan Province used to boast the highest forest coverage rate
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The change took place after a province-wide afforestation
project was launched in Fujian in 1989. In 1992 trees were planted
on almost all the mountains where trees could survive.
</P>
<P>
At present there are some 6.6 million ha of forests in the
province, with a timber reserve of 400 million cu m.
</P>
<P>
The province is often hit by typhoons so the coastal forest
shelterbelt system is an important prerequisite for economic
development in the coastal areas, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
So far, a 3,300-km green belt has taken shape along the
coastline of the province, and the forest coverage rate in the 27
coastal cities and counties has reached 43 percent. In addition,
the afforestation rate of 185 coastal townships has grown from
eight percent in 1988 to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Urban greening has been put on the agendas of all local
governments. Last year over 400 ha of green land was added to the
cities in the province, bringing the urban afforestation rate up
to 28.4 percent. This capital city of the province spent more than
22 million yuan improving afforestation along traffic arteries
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Rules to Allow Goal-keeper Move at Penalties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Football Board
ruled on Saturday at Eelfast that goal-keepers will be allowed to
move along their line at penalties.
</P>
<P>
The board also ruled that the keepers will no longer allowed to
handle the ball direct from a throw-in.
</P>
<P>
The board, which includes four members from the British
associations and four from FIFA, also issued a directive to
referees that keepers will only be permitted to hold on to the
ball for a maxium of six seconds after getting hold of it.
</P>
<P>
The keepers will be only allowed to take four steps with the
ball in their hands before having to release it.
</P>
<P>
The new rules is aim at fasten the pase of soccer match. Under
the new rules, an indirect free kick will be awarded if the
goal-keepers handles the ball after receiving it directly from a
throw in.
</P>
<P>
The new rules will come into effect on July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
