<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgian Wins Het Volk Cycling Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Peter Van Petegem of Belgium took
the title of the 200-kilometer Het Volk cycling race at Ghent,
Belgium, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Van Petegem, unfavored before the race, broke clear four
kilometers from the finish line to win the race in five hours and
eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Tom Steels, also from Belgium, finished
second with six seconds behind Petegem.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the race, Wim Omloop and Jan Poppe from Belgium and
Jacky Durand of France broke free and took a lead of nearly 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
But they could not hold on and faded in the second half of the
race. Richard Virenque and Sebastien Medan of France took the
chance to catch them.
</P>
<P>
Seven riders led the race with 30 kilometers to go before Van
Petegem broke away in the last four kilometers to take the title.
</P>
</TEXT>
