<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Faces Massive Anti-Nuclear Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 1 (Xinhua) -- About 10,000 anti-nuclear protesters
gathered in the northern German city of Lueneberg today to protest
against a cross-country transportation of nuclear wastes to a
nearby storage depot at Gorleben.
</P>
<P>
A special train loaded with 750-ton nuclear wastes gathered
from two nuclear power plants in southern Germany and from France
will start from the west German town of Walheim on Monday, and
arrive at Gorleben, some 70 kilometer east of Lueneberg, for
storage on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The cross-country shipping has triggered off massive protests
in Germany over the past week and has invoked the biggest postwar
police mobilization in the country in which 30,000 policemen were
involved.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the coal power plant at Walheim, where the nuclear
wastes were loaded on the train and await transportation, were
guarded by thousands of policemen.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the local government at Lueneberg also declared a
ban on demonstrations in close vicinity to the railway lines.
</P>
<P>
However, German media still expect massive resistance by
anti-nuclear activists in coming days.
</P>
<P>
Saturday also saw protesting farmers from the Gorleben area
block the Lueneberg city centre with over 100 tractors. The
protest was however peaceful and demonstrators backed down from an
initial call to stage a sit-in on the railway tracks.
</P>
<P>
Protesters on Saturday also occupied two gymnastics halls near
Gorleben which are to be used as accommodation for police. They
were later forcibly dispersed by policemen.
</P>
<P>
German authorities said the security costs for the
transportation would run up to some 100 million German marks, or
about 60 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Much of the traditional anti-nuclear protest in Germany has
taken the form of peaceful demonstrations or sit-ins on railway
lines.
</P>
<P>
But there has also been a growing violent trend with extremists
tearing out railway tracks and sabotaging overhead railway power
lines.
</P>
<P>
Police said they expect to encounter about 1,000 violent
protesters in the Gorleben region next week, local media reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0241 </DOCNO>
