<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Rallies Arab Support to Defend Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat today urged a united Arab front to
defend Jerusalem, which is under threat from Israel's settlement
expansion in the holy city of Islam.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an ongoing emergency meeting of the Arab League
(AL) Council on the repercussions of the Israeli housing plan,
Arafat called it "nothing but an attempt to undermine the peace
process."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Ministerial Committee on Jerusalem Affairs endorsed
an agreement Wednesday on establishing 6,500 housing units for the
Jewish settlers in Gabal Abu Ghoneim, known to Israel as Har Homa,
a tree-covered hill taken by Israel from Jordan in the 1967
Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
"There is no peace without Jerusalem," he said, adding that
the measure is aimed at dividing the West Bank into northern and
southern parts and building a new Bethlehem. The new homes will
be built between East Jerusalem and the PNA-ruled Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
Israel's decision has sparked criticism from its key ally the
United States and Palestinian warnings that it could unleash
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
Arafat called upon the Arab leaders to side with the
Palestinian people and defend the holy Jerusalem. He urged them
"not to leave the Palestinian people alone in the face of the
monstrous Israeli settlement."
</P>
<P>
Arafat said in his speech that the envisaged housing project
flagrantly violates international resolutions and the Oslo
agreements, signed between the Palestinians and the Israelis, and
stumbles the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo agreement, Israelis and the Palestinians are to
settle the status of Jerusalem and other sensitive issues in the
peace negotiations set for March to determine the final status of
the territories occupied by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the meetings, AL Secretary General Esmat
Abdul-Meguid denounced Israel's settlement activities in the
occupied Arab lands and continued confiscation of Palestinian
lands.
</P>
<P>
He said that the action aimed at confronting
settlement-building and resisting campaigns to Judaize Jerusalem
has a basis in international law and agreements.
</P>
<P>
"Arabs will never relinquish their rights," the AL chief vowed
at the emergency session.
</P>
<P>
Fiercely attacked by Arabs, the European Union and the
U.S. alike, the construction plan is regarded as an attempt to
cement Israel's hold over Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want
to have as the capital of their future independent state.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have warned flare-ups of anti-Israeli
violence in the West Bank and Gaza reminiscent of clashes that
erupted last September when Israel opened a new entrance to an
archaeological tunnel near Muslim holy sites in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who arrived here early today, also discussed the
Jewish settlement in Jerusalem with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak. He will fly to Washington on Sunday for talks with
U.S. President Bill Clinton and U.S. Secretary of State Madeline
Albright. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Ankara-Tehran Diplomatic Ties in Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Ankara-Tehran diplomatic
relations are experiencing hard times as the two governments have
decided to kick out each other's top envoys in a week's time.
</P>
<P>
But both sides have shown positive signs to save the
relationship from aggravating into a real crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry announced today that Turkish
Ambassador Osman Koruturk and Consul General Ufuk Ozsancak should
leave Iran in a tit-for-tat move against the Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish consul general in Iran's northwestern city of
Orumieh was declared by the Iranian government as persona
non-grata for his involvement in activities inconsistent with
diplomatic norms.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Ambassador to Ankara Mohammad Reza Baqeri and Consul
General to Istanbul Mohammad Reza Rashedi were expelled from
Turkey last week for their statement about Islam and
fundamentalism. Then came the expulsion order Friday to Saeed
Zare, Iranian Consul General to Erzurum, who was called a persona
non grata by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The latest tension between Ankara and Tehran stems from
February 1 address given by Baqeri.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish press accused Baqeri of having overstepped the
bounds of his diplomatic duties for openly speaking in favor of
an Islamic rule in the secular Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Attending the anti-Israeli Quds (Jerusalem) International Day
ceremonies in Sincan, an Turkish city district, Baqeri asked his
Turkish audience if they would like to support the rule of Islam.
</P>
<P>
After Baqeri's lecture was publicized, the Turkish media and
secular politicians charged that the Iranian ambassador had
intervened in the domestic affairs of Turkey by promoting Islamic
rule.
</P>
<P>
But, no sooner had Tehran and Ankara announced their orders to
expel each other's diplomats than they showed their willingness
for saving the relationship from turning really sour for the good
of their countries' security and economy, observers here noted.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Javad Larijani, Vice-Chairman of the Iranian
Parliament Foreign Policy Commission, said at a press conference
held here today that "I have no sense of worry about future of our
ties. Our ties with Turkey is very firm and will be expanding in
the future."
</P>
<P>
In Ankara today, Turkish President Suleyman Demirel sent out a
special envoy carrying a good-will message to Iranian President
Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani calling for improving the bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said in his message that Turkey and Iran should protect
their mutual security interests.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are also trying to boost their economic
links. Rafsanjani signed seven memoranda of understanding with
Turkey during his four-day visit to Ankara last December.
</P>
<P>
Among cooperative projects is a multi-billion-dollar gas energy
agreement to provide energy-starved Turkey with Iran's abundant
gas reserves for the next 22 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
