<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pledges to Assist Mexico in Combating Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today, praising Mexican government's efforts in combating drug
smuggling, pledged to do whatever possible to help the neighboring
country success against powerful drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly radio address, Clinton also said that he will
continue to pressure Mexico for "tough action" to keep drugs out
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's remarks came a day after he recertified Mexico in its
anti-drug program despite opposition from lawmakers, who attacked
Mexico on corruption in the anti-drug program.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Clinton praised Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo's efforts in battling Mexican drug cartels seeking to
corrupt the country's law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
"President Zedillo has taken brave action, firing more than
1,200 tainted officials, extraditing criminals for the first time,
passing tough laws and arresting in his own drug czar for
corruption," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must do whatever we can to give (Mexico) the means to
succeed. Stamping out the drug trade is a long-term battle.... We
will continue to press our Mexican partners to take tough action
that will protect all our people from drugs," he added.
</P>
<P>
The president said that Mexico has a serious drug problem, but
"Mexico's leaders recognize that problem, and they have the will
to fight it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
