<DOCNO> XIE19970302.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Denounces Israeli Housing Plan in Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) Council today
issued a strong-worded denouncement against Israel's decision to
build new settlements in Gabal Abu Ghoneim in Eastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli new construction project violates the bases on
which the Mideast peace process is founded, all signed peace
agreements with the Palestinians and the letters of guarantee
offered by the U.S. to the Arab parties in Madrid," said the
statement, issued by the Arab League emergency session tonight.
</P>
<P>
The emergency meeting was held in the wake of Israel's
endorsement Wednesday of establishing 6,500 housing units for the
Jewish settlers in Gabal Abu Ghoneim, known to Israel as Har Homa,
a tree-covered hill taken by Israel from Jordan in the 1967
Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
The council warned that the Israeli decision and previous
settlement practices would threaten the peace march and thrust the
area into a quagmire of conflicts and instability.
</P>
<P>
It expressed its support for resolutions issued during past
Arab summits, the last of which was held in Cairo last June.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo summit reiterated the Arabs commitment to the
realization of a just and all-out peace based on international
legitimacy and the land-for-peace principle stressing the fact
that peace is the only strategic option.
</P>
<P>
The statement also pledges support to the Palestinians in
confronting the Israeli settlement schemes and calls for halt of
assistance to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat, while
addressing the session, urged a united Arab front to defend
Jerusalem, which is under threat from Israel's settlement
expansion in the third holiest city of Islam.
</P>
<P>
Fiercely attacked by Arabs, EU and the U.S. alike, the
envisaged project is regarded by Arabs as an attempt to cement
Israel's hold over Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want to have
as the capital of a future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Israel's decision has sparked Palestinian warnings that it
could unleash bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo agreement, Israel and the Palestinians are to
settle the status of Jerusalem and other sensitive issues in the
peace negotiations set for March to determine the final status of
Occupied Territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
